\par\par \b \uc2 Fighting graft a global  \highlight22\uc2 public \highlight\uc2  good   \b0\par\par\uc2 Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala , Nusa Dua, Bali   \par \uc2 664 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 February 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The high development cost of corruption is something almost everyone agrees on today. It takes a disproportionate toll on the poor, by undermining the delivery of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  services, creates macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , taints the financial sector, and worsens the investment climate.   \par \par \uc2 Moving up from the lowest end of the corruption perception distribution to a position right in the middle of the pack may result in an increase in investment by as much as 8 percent of GDP. Similarly, the per capita income growth may rise by over 1 per cent. But the real cost of corruption should be measured by the effect it has on human lives.   \par \par \uc2 Every US$100 million of stolen assets restituted to a developing country could fund full immunization for 4 million children, or approximately 250 thousand water connections for households, or 50-100 million Artemisinin based treatments for malaria.   \par \par \uc2 Now that there is widespread recognition of the development impact of corruption, the fundamental question has become: How do we go about solving this problem? Good governance is a global \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  good that requires collective action. The landmark United Nations Convention against Corruption is the single most important international agreement reflecting this idea.   \par \par \uc2 The Convention provides an unprecedented step forward in recognizing the global responsibility in fighting corruption. Collective action against corruption requires the need to balance the burden of responsibilities. This is another fundamental point in the fight against corruption that has been overlooked.   \par \par \uc2 For too long the focus of anticorruption efforts has targeted developing countries. Corruption in developing countries is also the result of an enabling and permissive global environment. All countries are responsible for this environment, particularly those with greater \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political leverage.   \par \par \uc2 Developing countries might have a long way to go in improving transparency, accountability, and good governance. However, progress made by these countries will be deemed insufficient, as long as the international financial architecture provides a risk-free alternative for the concealment of stolen funds.   \par \par \uc2 Viewed in this way, the failure of the international community to solve this situation actually undermines the efforts undertaken by developing countries. Though numbers are hard to come by, an estimated $20-40 billion each year leaves developing countries as illicit flows of which a significant portion is corruptly stolen funds.   \par \par \uc2 There can be no free-riding in the fight against corruption. Governments, the private sector, civil society groups, the international media, international organizations need to live up to their commitments. They can't wait for the action of others as a precondition to start fulfilling their duties.   \par \par \uc2 Developed countries can step-up the pace and undertake decisive and creative measures to facilitate the recovery of stolen assets. Developing countries can also make substantial progress by establishing independent anti corruption bodies, implementing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  asset declarations for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials, and establishing transparent, competitive and objective procurement systems.   \par \par \uc2 Governance and anticorruption and development are a single agenda. It is the agenda based on the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  being served by government. The international community needs to do everything possible to help countries to fight poor behavior by building strong institutions. But this effort must be matched by actions in developed country financial centers to make bad behavior easier to detect and easier to rectify. Let's hope that this Bali meeting will be a turning point in our common efforts.   \par \par \uc2 The Conference of State Parties to the United Nations Convention against Corruption should call on the global community to work aggressively and in global partnership to achieve the full promise of the Convention. The World Bank needs to play its part in this global collective effort.   \par \par \uc2 The institution is an ally through its governance and anti-corruption action plan that looks to stamp out corruption and through the Stolen Asset Recovery Initiative to help developing countries in recovering stolen assets. President Zoellick has made the fight against corruption a central plank of his tenure.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is Managing Director, World Bank Group.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080201e4210000m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
