\par\par \b \uc2 Revising the state  \highlight22\uc2 budget \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 765 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 February 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Very rarely has our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  faced so many inimical factors causing converging \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  as it does now. So drastic have been the changes in global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions and financial markets that the Indonesian government is being forced to amend its 2008 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  only one month after its implementation. Normally any changes to the annual state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  are proposed to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  early in the second semester of the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year.   \par \par \uc2 A \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  certainly is not self-contained, operating in a vacuum. It is influenced by external factors and entrenched patterns of expenditures, inflation and structural imbalances between expectations and resources.   \par \par \uc2 The government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  apparently had not expected such dramatic changes to the external factors. When the 2008 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  bill was approved by the House in mid-October 2007, the aggregate revenue and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  figures were not substantially different from the amounts proposed by the government, except for the special appropriation of Rp 7 trillion (US$750 million) as a contingency fund in anticipation of additional expenditures in the wake of rising global oil prices.   \par \par \uc2 Neither the government nor the House saw any need to change the assumptions used by the government for the key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators in the 2008 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 : \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6.8 percent, 6 percent inflation, Rp 9,100 average rupiah exchange rate, 7.5 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  benchmark interest rate, $60/barrel average oil price and oil production of 1.034 million barrels/day.   \par \par \uc2 However, the impact of the weakening global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and international credit crunch, resulting from the subprime mortgage crisis in the United States, international oil prices that have persistently approached $100/barrel since the last quarter of last year and the steep rise in domestic food commodity prices, has made irrelevant the basic assumptions for most major items of revenue and \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Oil prices have remained mostly over $90 per barrel and the damage inflicted by the American subprime crisis has turned out to be more devastating than earlier estimated, thereby worsening the international credit crunch and causing the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth estimate to be lowered to 1.54 percent from 1.9 percent. Indonesian oil production is estimated at only 910,000 barrels per day, much less than the 1.034 million barrels/day originally assumed in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The government has prepared a set of contingency measures to control the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at Rp 90 trillion, or 2.1 percent of gross domestic product, compared to Rp 73.3 trillion or 1.7 percent of GDP as stipulated in the approved \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati explained that without the contingency measures the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  could skyrocket to Rp 185.4 trillion, or 4.3 percent of GDP. A \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of such magnitude would significantly increase the country's sovereign risks and consequently raise its borrowing costs, while the government plans to raise Rp 103 trillion from rupiah and dollar bonds this year, or 12.5 percent more than originally planned.   \par \par \uc2 However, we doubt the contingency measures the government has been mulling over since late last year are sufficient to cope with the adverse impact of the unfavorable external factors cited above, because the measures focus on austerity and \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline and management -- so far the main weaknesses of the government.   \par \par \uc2 None of the measures is designed to significantly reduce fuel consumption and increase fuel conservation and efficiency. The proposed \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  revisions instead increase fuel consumption from 35.8 million kiloliters to 39 million kiloliters, even though most estimates put \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year at 6.5 percent, lower than the government projection of 6.8 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Consequently fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  will more than double to Rp 116 trillion and the electricity subvention nearly double to Rp 54 trillion.   \par \par \uc2 The government expects savings of Rp 30 trillion from a 15 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut at all ministries, and will squeeze an additional Rp 7 trillion in dividend payments from state companies and increase borrowing from the financial market by Rp 11.5 trillion.   \par \par \uc2 But we do not yet see any sense of urgency on the part of the government. Without a sense of crisis it will most likely be business as usual within the whole government.   \par \par \uc2 Without a lot more \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline, the government will not be able to achieve its savings target. Without better \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  management, the more than 50 percent increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  appropriations for capital \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to almost $17 billion this year will not materialize for pump priming, while domestic consumption is expected to be the main driver of growth this year.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080204e4240000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
