\par\par \b \uc2 Govt to revise down  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  growth on rising oil, food prices   \b0\par\par\uc2 Aditya Suharmoko , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 438 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 February 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The government confirmed Friday a plan to revise the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target down from the 6.8 percent stated in the 2008 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid soaring global prices for oil and staple food commodities.   \par \par \uc2 "A downward revision is a must, but we will consider all the plus and minus factors," Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati told reporters as quoted by Antara newswire Friday. However, she declined to give an exact figure for the new forecast.   \par \par \uc2 On Monday, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  said the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would grow between 6.2 percent and 6.8 percent this year.   \par \par \uc2 Mulyani said the latest forecast on the country's macroeconomic fundamentals showed mounting inflationary pressure as domestic consumption continued to suffer from global price increases.   \par \par \uc2 "The rising price of staple foodstuffs will hurt the people's purchasing power," she said.   \par \par \uc2 Last month, the country's inflation rate reached to a 16-month high, with a 1.77 percent increase, due to the price rises for key commodities, such as rice, wheat and soybeans.   \par \par \uc2 The changes have prompted the government to review its assumptions on key variables -- particularly oil prices -- in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  while issuing new regulations last week to stabilize prices. These include various \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives for the food industry.   \par \par \uc2 Facing criticism for its late response, the government announced Wednesday a plan to revise its assumption for oil prices to $83 a barrel from $60 a barrel in the 2008 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The change comes only 36 days after implementation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Crude oil prices surpassed $60 per barrel in mid 2006. They are currently hovering around $90 per barrel after peaking at $100 in early January.   \par \par \uc2 The Finance Ministry's latest calculations estimate the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  to reach Rp 87.3 trillion (about $9.45 billion), or 2 percent of growth domestic product (GDP), increasing from 1.7 percent in the current state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Mulyani also confirmed, the government would propose a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  revision to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  in mid February. It expects the process will conclude in March.   \par \par \uc2 In normal conditions, a state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is revised in the second semester. The revisions to the key assumptions, many economists said, were a result of poor \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  forecasting by the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  team, which has led to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 A head economist at the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Faisal Basri, said his team had identified the coming threat of skyrocketing oil prices as early as 2006, but their warning was not taken seriously by the government.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080209e4290001a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
