\par\par \b \uc2 Order, growth and democracy   \b0\par\par\uc2 G. Adi Kusuma , Blacksburg, VA   \par \uc2 1,003 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 February 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 It has been more than a week since the death of former president Soeharto.   \par \par \uc2 His death has stirred controversy on various issues, including his legacy and position in Indonesia's history.   \par \par \uc2 Some condemned his actions and policies during his presidency, especially when those policies are related to human rights and democratic issues.   \par \par \uc2 Yet, his achievements would be romanticized by those who benefited greatly from his \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development achievements and the national stability and order.   \par \par \uc2 Even several world leaders praised his ability to bring stability and growth to the region. And the former President is not alone.   \par \par \uc2 Let's take Vladimir Putin as another example. The Russian president was recently named Time Magazine's Person of the Year. for his success in bringing Russia out from disarray into order in his short time as the country's leader.   \par \par \uc2 This happened despite the fact even Time recognizes how his leadership style stifled democracy and caused dissent.   \par \par \uc2 Yet, despite his tough leadership style, the Russians support him overwhelmingly. His approval rating never dropped below 70 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Thus, the keywords seems to be order, stability and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  achievement, rather than democratic achievement.   \par \par \uc2 Indonesia's democratic experiment is not working well. This only shows there is no "one size fits all" jacket, even in a democracy itself.   \par \par \uc2 Loosely quoting Saint Thomas Aquinas, everything has to be culturally and contextually fit into the new culture, in this case a nation.   \par \par \uc2 Our pursuit of a Jeffersonian democracy has led the country to many problems.   \par \par \uc2 Our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development and growth lacks behind our neighbors.   \par \par \uc2 Political turf-war seems to be a priority rather than the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest. And corruption is now spread into all levels and branches of government, rather than being contained within certain levels or branches of government.   \par \par \uc2 Localities and provinces have to run deficits just to hold elections and they have to set aside so much money to "repay" the people who have paid the political leaders' campaign expenses, instead of using the money for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  goods and services.   \par \par \uc2 Some say we need to be patient with the democratic development in Indonesia. Yet, a globalized world does not have any patience.   \par \par \uc2 Everyone competes at lightning pace. In addition to this, unfortunately, respect for a nation comes from the ability to bring order and the achievement of its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and material wonders, not necessarily from its "democratic" achievement.   \par \par \uc2 And this could be a universally embedded bias.   \par \par \uc2 The world is in awe with past material achievements rather than community or other non-material achievements.   \par \par \uc2 One could not pass the opportunity to visit the Coliseum in Rome and admire it as one of the world's wonders, despite its horrific human tragedy.   \par \par \uc2 One could not stop the world's awe in the Great Wall of China, despite its staggering human costs.   \par \par \uc2 This is just to name a few. And thus, it seems that we, human beings, have a paradox.   \par \par \uc2 We want to keep talking about democracy, and at the same time put higher admiration on material and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  wonders and achievements, despite its "undemocratic" means.   \par \par \uc2 Much research has shown democracy has negative, or at least neutral, and not positive impacts on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 While \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth alone should not be the measurement of one nation's success, it has become one of the most important measures.   \par \par \uc2 A democracy needs an infrastructure that could ensure the stability of the nation.   \par \par \uc2 It is only prudent to ensure a democratic progress in Indonesia also remembers order and stability as part of its element.   \par \par \uc2 A hastened democracy would only lead to chaos and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the kind of chaos and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that brought back President Putin in Russia.   \par \par \uc2 That is also the kind of democratic chaos that brought then president Sukarno with his "Guided Democracy in the late 1950s and early 1960s" and the kind of democratic chaos that brought Soeharto into power for decades.   \par \par \uc2 Therefore, democracy in itself has to be gradual and evolutionary.   \par \par \uc2 In addition, people should not forget about duties and responsibilities, not merely rights afforded by a democracy.   \par \par \uc2 Using former president Soeharto as an example, while Indonesia needs to admit that Soeharto used a rather heavy pair of hands during his presidency, his achievements should not be brushed aside outright.   \par \par \uc2 His policies led to steady \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 While order, growth and democracy should not be put on opposite ends, the fact is we need order in order to talk about democracy, life and individual liberty.   \par \par \uc2 I would still argue for a continuing ascent to a democratic constitutional republic and I am proud of Indonesia's achievements in this decade of reform.   \par \par \uc2 In addition, I am not arguing against democracy in itself, nor am I arguing for a dictatorship.   \par \par \uc2 However, using a very simple argument that a friend of mine from Russia has, "How can you debate democracy when you are hungry and your people do not have anything to eat".   \par \par \uc2 I would also emphasize the need of bringing about stability and order.   \par \par \uc2 Being a pragmatist, Indonesia needs an order now, before we can further talk about democracy.   \par \par \uc2 And, whether we like it or not, Soeharto was able to secure one during his presidency.   \par \par \uc2 Despite the controversies over his presidency, for various and sometimes legitimate reasons, Indonesia needs to understand that she can not import a Jeffersonian democracy without any gradual maturity on democracy and a contextualization of its application into Indonesia's culture.   \par \par \uc2 And one cannot speak on the issues of democracy without first having settled basic necessities and order.   \par \par \uc2 And, to have order, a tough leadership style is sometimes needed.   \par \par \uc2 It should be noted this kind of leadership style is the one that would still nurture the elements of democracy in the future. Besides, as Jean Paul Sartre once noted, "Well, I have dirty hands. Right up to the elbows. I've plunged them in filth and blood. Do you think you can govern innocently?"   \par \par \uc2 The writer is Ph.D candidate, graduate assistant office of capital assets and financial management, Virginia Tech.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080211e42b0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
