\par\par \b \uc2 Impact of slowdown in U.S.  \highlight22\uc2 uncertain \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 Andi Haswidi , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 594 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 February 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The extent to which Indonesia is going to be affected by a U.S.-led global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and difficult to forecast, a discussion among top economists showed in Jakarta on Tuesday.   \par \par \uc2 At a discussion hosted by the Centre for Strategic and International Studies, University of Indonesia Institute for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Social Research executive director Chatib Basri argued that unlike neighboring economies such as Singapore and Malaysia, Indonesia was relatively insulated from a downturn in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Citing data from past U.S. recessions, Chatib concluded a 1 percentage point decrease in U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would mean a 0.20 to 0.25 percentage point decrease here.   \par \par \uc2 "My baseline scenario for growth is 6.5 percent. Thus, if the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  slows down by one percentage point, the downward revision will be about 6.25 percent," he said before other speakers, including \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  senior deputy governor Miranda S. Goeltom and Trade Minister Mari E. Pangestu.   \par \par \uc2 If the slowdown had already started at the beginning of the year, he said, the impact would not be immediate as it would first hit East Asian countries such as China and India and then Indonesia by the third or fourth quarter.   \par \par \uc2 "The U.S. is definitely showing a slowdown. But technically it is not in a recession yet as growth has not yet reached negative numbers two quarters in a row," he said, adding that 6.5 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth was still within reach for Indonesia.   \par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, he said, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  forecasting had become more perilous as the global market had been showing rapid and often unexpected changes, forcing economists to constantly revise their estimates and conclusions.   \par \par \uc2 Miranda, on the other hand, argued 6.5 percent growth was "almost impossible", as all models by BI economists pointed at a bottom level of 6.2 percent.   \par \par \uc2 "Although we are already decoupling from the U.S. market, I think the impact of a weakening U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be faster than expected," she said.   \par \par \uc2 Citing the result of a meeting of \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  governors in January in Mumbai, she said U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth was going to be weaker than the 1.5 percent forecast, and instead closer to 1.3 percent.   \par \par \uc2 Not only threatened by an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, most countries in Asia would suffer from a spike of inflation, particularly those with volatile food prices such as Indonesia and India.   \par \par \uc2 "As January alone already marked a 1.77 percent increase in inflation, it would be unlikely to meet the government's target of plus/minus 5 percent inflation by the end of this year," she said.   \par \par \uc2 On the capital flows channel, she said, the current market jitters from the subprime mortgage losses had greatly influenced the risk appetite of investors.   \par \par \uc2 "The question now is how Indonesia can convert the short-term capital into a long-term investment so the country's balance of payments can be more sustainable," she said.   \par \par \uc2 Speaking last, Trade Minister Mari E. Pangestu said her ministry was already considering revising the 14.5 percent total exports growth target.   \par \par \uc2 "Our forecasting was made before a recession began to loom in the U.S. and before the recent spike in inflation led by staple food price increases. I mean, everybody was shocked by how sharp it was," she said.   \par \par \uc2 As food price-led inflation was now a global phenomenon, she said, all \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makers were responding by constraining exports and granting \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  or even \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rebates to consumers.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080220e42k00018\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
