\par\par \b \uc2 On why oil price assumption of $85 doesn't mark the spot   \b0\par\par\uc2 Helmi Arman , Analyst   \par \uc2 711 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 March 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The speculative premium on the prices of primary commodities may not subside anytime soon. This brings serious implications to Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The world's supply of non-renewable natural resources such as oil is indeed being depleted by the day.   \par \par \uc2 However the recent surge in primary commodity prices appears difficult to justify by supply concerns alone, particularly at a time when real demand for oil is expected to decelerate amid a weakening of global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.   \par \par \uc2 It appears the primary reason for the surge in oil prices is speculative in nature. Last year, many were expecting Asia to withstand an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn in the U.S. This was widely known as the decoupling theory in market jargon.   \par \par \uc2 However the consensus today appears to be that Asia is still to a certain degree dependent on how the world's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is faring.   \par \par \uc2 Emerging market stocks are faring no better than U.S. stocks.   \par \par \uc2 For example the composite indices in Korea (Kospi), Japan (Nikkei) and even the Philippines (PSE) have gone down by at least 20 percent since their highs in October last year, while the Dow has plunged by around 17 percent.   \par \par \uc2 The Indonesia Composite Index has been hanging on but even that was due to the surging performance of commodity-related stocks.   \par \par \uc2 In \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  times, investors usually fly their funds to quality-seeking assets deemed as having the lowest risk. U.S. treasury securities have usually been a destination for this urge to shun from risk; however this asset class is currently beset by two major concerns.   \par \par \uc2 First, considering the inflation rate in the U.S. is currently standing at more than 4 percent, it makes little sense to invest in U.S. Treasuries, which are only yielding 1.5 percent -- 3.5 percent p.a. (i.e. for bonds maturing in 2 to 10 years).   \par \par \uc2 In other words, the "real" yield on this asset class is now actually negative.   \par \par \uc2 Second, for non-U.S. investors, it is even more difficult to justify placing money for such skimpy returns given the prospects of continued depreciation of the U.S. dollar.   \par \par \uc2 Note that since mid-2007 the U.S. dollar has weakened by more than 15 percent against the Japanese yen and more than 20 percent against the euro. And given the U.S. current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  has only begun to adjust, there might be more where that came from.   \par \par \uc2 Under these conditions it is no wonder primary commodities, some of which have store value qualities (such as gold), have been in high demand.   \par \par \uc2 In the month of February alone, commodity prices on average rose by nearly 20 percent, based on Bahana Securities' commodity price index.   \par \par \uc2 The big question is: will this trend continue?   \par \par \uc2 Judging from data covering the past 50 years, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  contractions in the U.S. usually last between six to 16 months.   \par \par \uc2 Given the severity of the current problems in the housing sector, expecting the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to bottom-out before the end of 2008 would be far from a safe bet.   \par \par \uc2 So if the past is anything to go by, we should expect U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data to still show a softening trend in the months to come.   \par \par \uc2 The Federal Reserve may continue to respond by cutting rates, thereby accentuating the decline in the U.S. dollar. In this regard, the key ingredients for a continued influx into the commodities market may prevail, and the speculative premium for commodities may stay elevated.   \par \par \uc2 This flight to commodities brings serious implications for the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial markets.   \par \par \uc2 High commodity prices will continue to up the pressure on domestic consumer prices, and will make the task of sustaining domestic consumer purchasing power much more difficult.   \par \par \uc2 It may also raise the government's cost of fundraising by casting \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over bond prices.   \par \par \uc2 The US$85 per barrel of oil price assumption, which was recently set for the 2008 government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , could soon be rendered obsolete.   \par \par \uc2 This is a concern for many bond investors, as it may lead to prospects of an even higher amount spent on fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a further widening \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at PT Bahana Securities   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080312e43c0001d\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The House Rejects Two BI Governor Candidates; President Asked to Submit New Names   \b0\par\par\uc2 630 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 March 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Members of the House have voted against the nomination of two \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) governor candidates, Agus Martowardojo and Raden Pardede, submitted by President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono.   \par \par \uc2 Fifty of 51 members-one could not attend the voting-of the House Commission XI were present at the closed voting. Of those present at the voting, 29 members rejected the two candidates, while 21 members voted for Agus Martowardojo. None of them voted for Raden Pardede.   \par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the House Commission XI Awal Kusumah informed the voting was closed, but democratic. Before the voting, several factions made lobbies.   \par \par \uc2 "Finally we agreed to make closed voting to make the identities of the voting members anonymous," he revealed at the press conference last night.   \par \par \uc2 Awal explained the House Commission XI would bring the result of the voting to the Conference Agency and the plenary meeting to later ask President Yudhoyono to submit new names.   \par \par \uc2 "The two candidates cannot be nominated again and the President has to submit new names. In accord with the Law, the President should submit maximum three names."   \par \par \uc2 According to him, if the House also rejected the new candidates, the President had to appoint the existing BI governor as the new governor.   \par \par \uc2 However, he continued, if the existing BI governor could not do his or her duty, he President could appoint BI senior deputy governor or BI deputy governor as the new governor.   \par \par \uc2 Vera Febyanti from the Democratic Faction was disappointed with the House rejection. However, she denied accusation saying the members of her faction were not solid.   \par \par \uc2 When asked about the possibility of the President submitting candidates from the internal environment of BI, Vera said the faction would need to have internal consolidation first.   \par \par \uc2 Dradjad H. Wibowo from the National Mandate Party (PAN) faction explained the rejection proved there was no money politics and political intervention in the nomination of BI Governor. "This proves there is no bribery."   \par \par \uc2 A member of the House Commission XI Rizal Djalil disclosed the result of the meeting would be reported to the plenary meeting on March 18.   \par \par \uc2 According to Rizal, the candidates submitted by the government should have clear track records. "The government should immediately submit new names. If the process is long, we are worried the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."   \par \par \uc2 Jamaludin Karim, Chairperson of the BPD faction, viewed the two candidates submitted by the government had weak monetary knowledge. "They are lacking of required capabilities, especially when answering questions from legislators about GDP, consumer price index, how to handle inflation, and how to boost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."   \par \par \uc2 Political interests   \par \par \uc2 The rejection took place when President Yudhoyono made a series of state visits to the Middle East and South Africa, which is scheduled to end on March 20, 2008.   \par \par \uc2 The result of the voting is considered shocking since, according to one foreign banker, the two candidates actually have capabilities and track records required to helm BI. The BI Governor, he added, didn't need to be experienced people since the board of BI governors had already been consisting of solid persons.   \par \par \uc2 In the meantime, a banking analyst viewed the rejection by the House showed the House prioritized political interests more than the capabilities and track records of the two candidates.   \par \par \uc2 "This means the capabilities and track records of the candidates are no longer important to them [legislators]."   \par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the Federation of Private Banks (Perbanas) Sigit Pramono regretted the rejection since it wasted more time.   \par \par \uc2 "Anyone nominated should have the same criteria of the BI governor, which are he or she should have competence, leadership, banking knowledge, monetary knowledge, and global knowledge. The sad thing is we should start the process from square one," inserted Sigit. (Bisnis/11/amu/ass/yn/asa)   \par \par \uc2 Document BIS