\par\par \b \uc2 Managing exchange risk amid volatility   \b0\par\par\uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta   \par \uc2 1,125 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 March 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Iran's President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad once decried the dollar as a" worthless piece of paper". Of course the value of the greenback is nowhere near that point yet. But the precipitous fall of the U.S. dollar last week has pushed its level to below 100 yen -- at one point it reached 96 yen -- and to below one Swiss franc, a level not seen since the mid 1990s.   \par \par \uc2 The extreme volatility in the currency market resulting from the credit crisis in the U.S. is being reflected in the wild swing of U.S. dollar exchange rates against other major currencies. Those who are exposed to exchange risk, whether in the form of assets or liabilities, are facing intricate problems of how to better manage this risk to avoid losses. These risks are not specific to corporate sectors.   \par \par \uc2 As the aftermath of the credit crisis in the U.S. is still unfolding, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  hang over the direction of the currency market, and the risk of foreign exchange exposure all of a sudden weighs heavily on central banks all over the world. They together have accumulated almost $6 trillion in \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 Central  \b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  of China\uc2 , which is sitting on a $1.4 trillion reserve, must be facing an acute dilemma. It can sit idly by and watch its dollar assets crumble, or it can dump its dollar holdings immediately, pushing the dollar into a tailspin. If this happens, it would be a disaster of unprecedented scale for the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 How would this turmoil in the currency market affect the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? The effects would come in three ways: through trade, the government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  reserve. The U.S. only supplies 9 percent of Indonesian imports. But around one third of Indonesian imports come from strong currency countries like the EU and Japan.   \par \par \uc2 China, whose currency, the yuan, is posed to appreciate, is becoming a major supplier of Indonesian imports with its 15 percent share. With this pattern of trade, it is clear raw materials imported from these countries would be more expensive for Indonesian manufacturing industries.   \par \par \uc2 The wild fluctuation in currency exchange rates would also adversely affect the Indonesian government \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  if not handled properly. Already beset by mounting fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the 2008 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  would bear more burden from the government's external debts denominated in strong currencies that have been appreciating against the U.S. dollar. A higher debt service burden could not be avoided because a sizable part of government debts are denominated in these currencies.   \par \par \uc2 The Indonesian government's external debt stood at US$81.2 billion at the end of 2007. But out of this amount, only 52 percent was denominated in U.S. dollar. The rest is denominated in strong currencies like the euro and yen. Last week, these currencies appreciated around 5-6 percent against the dollar.   \par \par \uc2 This means that in only one week, the government debt in euro and yen rose by $2 billion, or the equivalent of Rp 18 trillion. This is not an insignificant amount for a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  whose viability is being threatened by ballooning oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . To cover the widening \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government could cut \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on routine expenditures, education, health and infrastructure. But it cannot cut debt service payments that fall due.   \par \par \uc2 In preparing the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft every year the government only makes assumption on the rupiah exchange rate against U.S. dollar, and does not specifically make assumptions on U.S. dollar exchange rates against other major currencies. This is a bit of a mistake since rates among major world currencies are bound to fluctuate -- sometimes wildly -- which could heavily influence the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .   \par \par \uc2 Therefore it is important for the government to make specific assumptions on U.S. dollar exchange rates against major currencies in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to make the budgeted figures more realistic.   \par \par \uc2 The demise of the U.S. dollar will also impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)'s foreign exchange reserve. BI is currently sitting on a $55 billion reserve, a record amount. Most of this, or around 70 percent, is invested in U.S. Treasury notes.   \par \par \uc2 The dollar's plunge and continuing cut in Federal Reserve discount rates have resulted in a decline in the value of the BI reserve. Valued against currencies such as the Japanese yen or euro, the BI reserve is currently worth $2 billion less than a week ago.   \par \par \uc2 These losses occur at the time when BI is struggling to reduce interest burden it pays to Bank Indonesian certificate (SBI) holders. The outstanding SBI stood at Rp 268 trillion at the end of 2007, a 30 percent rise over the same period last year. The SBI is still one of the favorite investments for investors who are having difficulty in finding attractive returns for their funds. Rapid accumulation of SBI is a by-product of BI policies in the past.   \par \par \uc2 In order to protect exporters from too much rupiah appreciation, BI since 2005 has frequently conducted interventions in the money market by purchasing U.S. dollar. Between September 2005 and August 2007, these purchases amounted to $21 billion. But because these actions could be inflationary, BI had to sterilize the rupiah it pumped into the market by issuing more SBIs with attractive rates.   \par \par \uc2 Even though the spread between SBI rates and the yield of U.S. Treasury notes has narrowed because of several cuts in BI rates, with a 4 percent yield on U.S. Treasury notes -- and still declining -- the negative spread still incurs high costs for BI.   \par \par \uc2 BI still maintains a small fraction of its reserve in gold. This is unfortunate since the price of this metal has soared from $500 per troy ounce three months ago to $1,015 last week. BI might regret that gold is a mere 3.5 percent of its portfolio, too small to function as a buffer against the declining value of its dollar reserve.   \par \par \uc2 Developments in the currency market are moving rapidly, and because it is difficult to predict the direction of the market, a new paradigm in reserve management is called for. The first instinct of a \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  in managing its currency reserve is to take a conservative stance and avoid risk.   \par \par \uc2 But this approach is only appropriate in normal conditions. But in times of turmoil, where normal relationships among market forces are crumbling, the conventional way of managing exchange risk could result in the lost opportunity of making gains.   \par \par \uc2 Managing exchange risk needs foresight, better forecasting and a willingness to undertake calculated risk. Unless both BI and the government realize this, they will be unable to avoid suffering losses from their foreign exchange exposures.   \par \par \uc2 The writer is an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  analyst.   \par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080325e43p0000j\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Banks Choose Bilateral Loans   \b0\par\par\uc2 647 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 March 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The banking industry plans to shift the plan to issue global bond into the plan to ask for bilateral loans following the increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the global financial market. Until yesterday, several banks had made requests for a total US$5.37 billion (around IDR49.4 trillion) in loan to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI).   \par \par \uc2 State-owned banks ask for the largest loan of US$2.14 billion, followed by foreign and composite banks (US$1.72 billion), and national private banks (US$1.51 billion).   \par \par \uc2 The national banking industry makes the shift after their plan to issue global bond is curbed by the increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the global financial market. On the other hand, they really need foreign currencies to service due debts or to finance business expansion.   \par \par \uc2 BI Deputy Director of International Dian Ediana Rae revealed the turbulent global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions had made national banks think twice before issuing bonds.   \par \par \uc2 "\b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  global financial market has made banks reluctant to issue global bond since they are worried the cost of operation will be expensive," Dian said to Bisnis in Jakarta yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 Previously, several national banks-consisting of three state-owned banks and two private banks-had asked permission to issue global bonds worth US$1.3 billion.   \par \par \uc2 However, continued Dian, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  up to the moment had only approved US$500 million. In addition, inserted Dian, the related parties so far had yet realized the plan.   \par \par \uc2 Dian explained the need for foreign currencies usually came up in the second semester to finance business expansion and refinance debts. Dian further reminded that banks should be careful if they wanted to realize their plan in the second semester.   \par \par \uc2 According to Dian, the turbulent \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  started from the sub-prime mortgage crisis in the US, which was followed by soaring commodity prices. The crisis later had triggered the Federal Reserve to cut rate to curb inflation.   \par \par \uc2 "The crisis probably starts from there [subprime mortgage crisis], from the soaring oil price, and from the Fed rate cut."   \par \par \uc2 The total amount of bilateral loans asked by domestic banks this year increase significantly from US$1.96 billion in 2007. Last year, the amount of loan borrowed and realized by banks reached IDR14.3 trillion.   \par \par \uc2 Dian disclosed in 2007 no single banks submitted plans to issue global bonds.   \par \par \uc2 Delay plan   \par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Head Treasury of Bank Mandiri Sugiarto confirmed that Mandiri delayed the plan to seek funds from global bonds due to turbulent world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions.   \par \par \uc2 This year, Bank Mandiri requests for US$300 million in foreign-currency loans, but Sugiarto could not say when the plan would be realized. He also declined to expose the amount of bilateral loans that Mandiri targeted to have.   \par \par \uc2 Recently, Mandiri has got bilateral loan commitments worth US$700 million from four foreign financial institutions. The loans will be used to refinance due debts and to finance business expansion.   \par \par \uc2 Another bank seeking foreign currencies is Bank Negara Indonesia (BNI). The bank requires US$550 million, US$150 of which has already been obtained from Standard Chartered Bank.   \par \par \uc2 BRI is also preparing a plan to raise US$150 million to finance sub-debt that will mature in October 2008.   \par \par \uc2 Sukatmo Padmosukarso, Vice President Director of BII, admitted the bank this year sought US$100 million in foreign loans. "We will execute the plan this year if the market is good since we need the fund for balance management."   \par \par \uc2 Business Head Treasury of Bank Danamon Alfin Tolib told the bank was waiting for the market to calm down first before realizing its plan to issue bonds worth IDR1.2 trillion. He added the bank had yet had any plan to seek foreign loans.   \par \par \uc2 Aviliani, an economist at Indef, warned BI should be prudent in giving permit to banks to borrow foreign currency since this could affect rupiah liquidity and macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions. (Bisnis/11)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080326e43q00001\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Rupiah Declines by 1.8% in March   \b0\par\par\uc2 327 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 March 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Rupiah, the local currency, has declined by 1.8% during March, the worst monthly performance since November 2007, as investors have bough dollar to cover their end of month transaction.   \par \par \uc2 The depreciation of rupiah was in line with the record high of crude oil price at US$111.8 per barrel on March 17. The oil price hike would push inflation so that interest rate cut will be unlikely.   \par \par \uc2 The consumer price index has jumped by 7.4% last February year on year, the largest annual inflation in the last 16 months.   \par \par \uc2 Rupiah declined by 0.1% yesterday to IDR9.215 per dollar. In one week the depreciation is 0.5% from IDR9.170 per dollar. "The main reason is the end of month demand from corporate sector, while oil price is still threatening," said Wiling Bolung, the Head of Treasury of ANZ Panin Bank as quoted by Bloomberg yesterday.   \par \par \uc2 Wiling projected rupiah will be traded at IDR9,200-IDR9,300 per US$.   \par \par \uc2 An analyst of Asia Kapitalindo Alfred Pakasi said rupiah may strengthen to IDR9,100 - IDR9,050 but it depends on the capital inflow to the capital market. If the inflow is lower the exchange rate may decline to IDR9,300 and the new equilibrium is IDR9,200.   \par \par \uc2 He said that the capital inflow is affected by the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . If the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is in crisis and the market does not well respond the solution of the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , The Fed, rupiah will be under pressure.   \par \par \uc2 He said the money has been moving to commodity investment. "Investors have been waiting and seeing. The investment is also only for short term on the global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  following the US recession."   \par \par \uc2 Euro, meanwhile, has posted its record high against pound-sterling at 79.14 cents per euro as the UK has reported that the consumer confidence index has been at the lowest level in the last 15 years. (Bisnis/Bes)   \par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080331e43t00037\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
