\par\par \b \uc2 China is important, but don't forget about Japan\b0\par\par\uc2 Rizal Sukma , Jakarta   \par \uc2 712 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 April 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Over the last five years or so, China has seemed to occupy a central place in many nations' foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  agendas. This is understandable due to the rapid rise of China as an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  powerhouse and a military power.\par \par \uc2 For some, the rise of China could be a potentially threatening phenomenon to the existing international order. For others, China's rise brings about an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  opportunity that needs to be tapped. In between these two views, many countries see China both as an opportunity and a challenge.\par \par \uc2 The recent foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  speech by Australia's Prime Minister Kevin Rudd also vindicated the centrality of China in the international system. In the speech, Rudd gave a rather detailed discussion on Australia's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  toward China. China was also on the itinerary of his first world trip together with the United States and Europe. Japan was curiously left out in his trip, and Japan was referred to almost as a footnote.\par \par \uc2 Australia is not the only country that seems to be fascinated by the rise of China and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political opportunities it has brought about, and will continue to bring about, to the world. Any discussion on the nature of contemporary world politics in the United States, Europe and East Asia tends to be dominated by the China question.\par \par \uc2 We, too, in Indonesia seem to have been fascinated by the same phenomenon. We restored diplomatic relations, frozen by the New Order government since 1967 due to China's interference in Indonesia's domestic affairs, only in August 1990. However, our relations with China have improved tremendously since 1998.\par \par \uc2 The imperative for improving relations with China had suddenly become a matter of urgency in any foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  discourse of the successive governments in Jakarta, from former presidents Abdurrahman Wahid and Megawati to President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono today.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cooperation -- especially in trade and investment -- has become an important part of our bilateral relations with China. By 1997, for example, Indonesia's total exports to China reached US$2.7 billion, a significant jump from only $834 million in 1990. By 2004, China had become the fifth-largest trading partner for Indonesia. In the same year, Indonesia's exports to China increased by 232 percent from 2003 amounting to $12.6 billion. The total volume of trade surged to $16.8 billion in 2005.\par \par \uc2 The basis for bilateral cooperation received a stronger impetus when, on April 25, 2005, Yudhoyono and Chinese President Hu Jintao signed an agreement to establish a "strategic partnership" between the two countries, laying the ground for a comprehensive cooperation on a wide range of issues, including energy, security and defense. This, as suggested by Yudhoyono during his trip to Beijing, was motivated primarily by our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests and needs.\par \par \uc2 The general view of China in Indonesia has also evolved. China is no longer seen as a threat, ready to destabilize Indonesia by exporting its communist ideology. While \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding China's long-term strategic intention in East Asia remains visible, China is now seen largely as an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  opportunity. While it is still a minority view, some have even suggested our relationship with China is important as a counterbalance to the preeminent role of the United States in global politics.\par \par \uc2 While the relationship with China is undoubtedly important, Indonesia should not make a mistake by forgetting Japan. Despite the growing importance of China, relations with Japan should continue to occupy an important place in our foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Japan is the largest trading partner and investor in Indonesia. Japan has been playing an important role in our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development. Japan is a fellow democracy with whom we share many values and norms.\par \par \uc2 This reminder is important because April 2008 marks the 50th anniversary of Indonesia-Japan relations. I wonder how many Indonesian leaders, policymakers, and politicians are aware of this important fact. Both Indonesia and Japan should celebrate this important occasion by focusing more on how to reinvigorate our relationship and how to chart a strategic direction for the future. We should not celebrate it merely by organizing cultural performances and exhibitions.\par \par \uc2 The writer is the deputy executive director of the Centre for Strategic and International Studies in Jakarta.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080415e44f0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
