\par\par \b \uc2 Oil  \highlight22\uc2 subsidies \highlight\uc2  fueling the rich, not poor\b0\par\par\uc2 Maxensius Tri Sambodo , Jakarta   \par \uc2 796 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 April 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  recently agreed on amendments to the 2008 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  with new macroeconomic assumptions. The government acknowledged, though, that the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  estimates could still change if the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition worsen, the international oil prices persistently hover above US$100/barrel, average Indonesian oil output falls below the target and food prices continue to rise.\par \par \uc2 Basically, these external factors have negative impacts on the stability of commodity, financial and labor markets in Indonesia, through the supply and demand side mechanism.\par \par \uc2 By dividing the sources of destabilizing, it is clear that most of the external factors are uncontrolled variables. This notwithstanding, the government fixed the prices (price rigidity) for many strategic commodities such as rice, oil for the transportation sector, gas and electricity with the consequences that the government has to put up \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to defend the the rigidity of the prices.\par \par \uc2 Basically, \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not make the market work properly, because commodity prices do not reflect the real cost or the scarcity of the products. As a result \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  capacity will determine how far the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  will go. Based on the latest \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  will rise to as high as 2.1 percent of gross domestic product.\par \par \uc2 At the same time, there are no clear and good exit strategies for reducing \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . In fact, the current energy \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is anti-poor. For example, in terms of reducing oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government will implement "smart cards" for subsidized gasoline users and accelerate the energy conversion program from kerosene to gas. However, it seems the costs of implementation of those policies are higher than the benefits because \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  are not allocated for the target group.\par \par \uc2 For instance, in many places where the kerosene conversion program was implemented, many people lined up for kerosene. Poor people have a different ability to adapt to \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  changes, depending on their background, education, experiences and occupation.\par \par \uc2 Urban poor people usually buy kerosene daily because of income \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and competing demands with other expenditures. This kind of consumption pattern is not accommodated into the conversion program. Further, the lack of supporting policies such as cash transfer for the poor or food \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  causes difficult transitions for the poor. High inflation together with low institutional capacity to implement the program cause poor people to become marginalized.\par \par \uc2 One can conclude from the oil \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that Indonesia is a heaven for rich people, because both rich and poor people can buy petroleum at the same price. This anomaly is very obvious when we look at how more rich people prefer to buy petroleum in \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  petrol stations, which sell subsidized and non-subsidized gasoline, rather than \uc2 Petronas\uc2  or Shell stations that sell only the non-subsidized.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, many rich people can enjoy luxurious facilities in their own car. The others have to stand in buses without air conditioning. This kind of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  paradox occurs because the government tends to use commodity price \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  instead of target group \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Basically, good \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs to shift from commodities to target group \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for reasons of equity.\par \par \uc2 Solving the problem of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  is a chicken or the egg dilemma. If government cuts fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , inflation will skyrocket with serious implications on the living costs of the people, notably the poor.\par \par \uc2 However, there are many other ways to reduce \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  through either a big bang or a gradual approach, each with its costs and benefits. A gradual approach would have a low impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  destabilization compared to the big bang.\par \par \uc2 What are the costs of implementing current fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 ?\par \par \uc2 First, it is clear the government loses an opportunity to convince people to use limited resources effectively and efficiently.\par \par \uc2 Second, there is a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  bias to the rich because the government has limited capacity to increase the capability of the poor. This causes such problems as social jealousy. Third, in the long run it depresses \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  capability.\par \par \uc2 It is true the government can finance \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  by issuing debts on both the domestic and international markets. But this borrowing spree will sharply increase the government's future debt obligations.\par \par \uc2 But there is room for the government to reduce the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and improve \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects in the future if it tries to shift commodity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the target group and uses savings from reduced \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to increase the capacity of the poor and build more \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  utilities.\par \par \uc2 The government's statement that it will "not to increase oil price until 2009" clearly indicates it underestimates the change in global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions and overestimates the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Research Center of the Indonesian Institute of Sciences and can be reached at mtsambodo@yahoo.com.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080417e44h0000o\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Surge in  \highlight22\uc2 Subsidy \highlight\uc2  Undermines Debt Service Capacity\b0\par\par\uc2 334 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 April 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Investors are worried the government will not be able to service its debts if it doesn't immediately raise fuel prices in the wake of the looming surge in fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 An economist at the Institute for Development of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Finance (Indef) Aviliani viewed if such worries from investors went unheeded, investors probably would dispose their T-bonds and Indonesian retail bonds (ORI.)\par \par \uc2 She warned the effect would exacerbate Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions ahead. "Investors want the government to raise fuel prices by 20%-30%. It should be no problem if the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not popular," she said yesterday.\par \par \uc2 According to Aviliani, the government should raise fuel prices gradually starting from June, instead of waiting for 2009 to apply higher fuel price hikes.\par \par \uc2 If the government didn't raise fuel prices, she added, \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would swell and the government might not be able to service its debts.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, Bloomberg reported the surge in global food prices probably would trigger investors to buy insurance products covering non-performing loans in Malaysia, Indonesia, and the Philippines.\par \par \uc2 Tim Condon, ING Bank Head of Research to Asia, revealed the swap on non-performing loan cost in the three Southeast Asian countries-where food and fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  represent 2% of GDP-would increase.\par \par \uc2 Food \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  are estimated to increase following the surge in rice wheat, corn, and soybean prices to their record highs.\par \par \uc2 "People are getting worried about the prospect of food scarcity and this creates political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."\par \par \uc2 Condon further forecasted the region would be vulnerable to food inflation and investors would shift from T-bonds to NPL swap to seek protection from the impacts of the crisis.\par \par \uc2 The UN records global food prices last month skyrocketed by 57% from the same period last year.\par \par \uc2 The Malaysian government on April 17 informed the country's fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would soar to at least MR40 billion (US$12.7 billion) this year from MR33 billion last year. (Bisnis/nom/16)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080426e44q00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscale