\par\par \b \uc2 Infrastructure projects must cope with fuel, steel price hikes\b0\par\par\uc2 Yenwy Wongso , Research Analyst   \par \uc2 747 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 May 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 14\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Indonesian performance on completing major infrastructure projects on time, or at all, is poor. There will be more delays as fuel and steel price hikes hit, unless project management improves to cope with these conditions.\par \par \uc2 Progress on infrastructure construction is limited, especially for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  projects. Government plans to raise fuel prices by an average 28.7 percent will increase \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the sector.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia may be the largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Southeast Asia, but for infrastructure it has become a never-never land where the only certainty is that it will take forever to finish a project.\par \par \uc2 If the country continues to under-perform like this, it might soon lose any competitive edge against neighboring countries such as Vietnam and Cambodia.\par \par \uc2 Recently, the President officially opened the Downtown WaruJuanda International Airport toll road in Surabaya, East Java. Started in 1996 the project was scheduled for completion in early 1999. The 1998 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis was blamed for the delays.\par \par \uc2 After struggling for nearly 12 years, the investor completed just 12 kilometers, only one third of the initial plan. Meanwhile, costs quadrupled due to land acquisition problems and inflation.\par \par \uc2 The Surabaya tollway is considered lucky to be completed at all compared to the Bekasi Cawang - Kampung Melayu tollway where construction started in 1997. The financial crisis was also blamed for this one, but it was never completed. Concrete piles for the elevated sections remain as monuments along the side of the West Tarum Drainage canal in Bekasi.\par \par \uc2 Less than 10 projects put forward in the 2005 Infrastructure Summit 2005 have started construction. Most of the rest are stuck at the prequalification and tender stages. None of the projects proposed during the 2006 summit has been built, or even reached the tender stage.\par \par \uc2 It is more than 10 years since the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis hit Indonesia. The contribution of construction toward GDP has gradually increased over the past five years, but has not reached precrisis levels yet. Construction as a share of GDP only reached 7.7 percent in 2007, slightly up on 7.2 percent in 2006 but still below the precrisis level of 8 percent.\par \par \uc2 Development of both \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and private infrastructure is required in order to boost the nation's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 However, infrastructure projects are susceptible to inflation of raw material prices, in particular cement and steel. With crude oil prices nearing US$120/barrel, potential raw material price increases could prove to be stronger than expected.\par \par \uc2 For instance, hot rolled coils (HRC) in the domestic market recently reached $1,027 per ton, up from $789 per ton in January this year, up 30 percent. Meanwhile, cement producers have increased selling prices for cement products by 5 - 15 percent in April, for example in one case from Rp 37,000 per 50-kilogram sack to Rp 42,000, an increase of 14 percent.\par \par \uc2 The surge in raw material prices has resulted in submitted cost estimates for construction projects becoming frequently outdated. This means that most projects which have already been tendered are having to review prices again.\par \par \uc2 To cope with soaring material prices, project owners or construction companies have come up with different strategies.\par \par \uc2 The most common strategy is to secure future contracts for raw material delivery throughout the entire construction period for new projects. This is commonly done by large construction companies to hedge against inflationary risks in material prices.\par \par \uc2 Second, construction companies will pass on price increases to project owners via cost escalation clauses in their contracts. This is common for government projects, mostly involving \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  infrastructure, such as \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  roads, toll roads, power plants, dams, irrigation, airports and harbors.\par \par \uc2 Accordingly, the \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Works Ministry takes into account increased construction costs whenever government implements a fuel price hike. The type of compensatory measure varies from cash or a top up payment through to the reduction of project scope (for example for road projects).\par \par \uc2 Project developers can also split up construction projects using several contractors to speed up implementation as a hedge against inflationary risks in material prices. This is also common in the construction of toll roads.\par \par \uc2 No matter what strategies are implemented to cope with rising costs of materials, infrastructure development must still go on. Otherwise the country's potential might be held back.\par \par \uc2 So long these mitigating strategies can be well implemented then the outlook for infrastructure construction might still be considered attractive, despite the increases in fuel and other costs.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080507e4570001i\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
