\par\par \b \uc2 The currency stability net\b0\par\par\uc2 The agreement reached Sunday by finance ministers from 13 Asian countries, including Indonesia, to create a pool of at least US$80 billion in foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  was a significant step toward a regional version of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).   \par \uc2 626 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 May 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The agreement, made in Madrid at the annual meeting of the Asian Development Bank, was in the interest of protecting participating countries' currencies.\par \par \uc2 The deal will replace the eight-year arrangement of bilateral currency swaps made in 2000 under the Chiang Mai Initiative and transform it into a more powerful self-managed reserve pooling mechanism governed by a single contract.\par \par \uc2 Under the Chiang Mai Initiative, only bilateral currency swaps were permitted, which meant a country seeking to swap multiple currencies had to obtain permission from each individual partner country, a time-consuming process.\par \par \uc2 Now the mechanism is multilateral.\par \par \uc2 The agreement was seemingly prompted by frustration from countries hit by the 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in dealing with the IMF. Indonesia, South Korea and Thailand were required to implement harsh and unpopular \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies in return for bailouts.\par \par \uc2 The pooling of foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  - timely, in view of global financial market \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , credit crunch and weakening world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 - may help prevent a repeat of the region's financial turmoil or a run on a member's currency, like those that took place in 1997-1998.\par \par \uc2 The purpose of the fund is to heal wounds before they become serious, should liquidity or financing problems arise. It would be like a first-aid measure providing care before the IMF gets in.\par \par \uc2 One may argue the situation now is much different from that before the 1997 crisis, especially where Indonesia is concerned. Before 1997, massive capital inflow went mainly to a few large corporations and banks which borrowed recklessly in defiance of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's warning. Now the lows are mostly channeled into financial markets, automatically spreading the risk to thousands of investors.\par \par \uc2 Hence, any sudden reversal will also spread losses across a broad investor base, resulting in small losses.\par \par \uc2 A multilateral swap arrangement is still needed, otherwise vulnerable countries will have to succumb to harsh treatment under the IMF bailout scheme.\par \par \uc2 The risk of such an arrangement is countries could become complacent, knowing they can draw down on the pool of \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to defend their currency. Hence, the \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be used responsibly and a surveillance mechanism should be improved to provide an early warning.\par \par \uc2 But what most countries in Asia are now facing is strikingly different from the height of the 1997-1998 crisis. The accumulation of \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to surging capital inflow and rising trade surpluses have made most central banks surpass the level of \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  deemed sufficient to counter external payment crises.\par \par \uc2 Many governments in Asia are encountering excess financial market liquidity, not \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  liquidity. Hence, what they currently need is not so much a beefed-up defense system, but more real cooperation among their central banks.\par \par \uc2 Thailand, in late 2006, gave us a glimpse of what could happen. Faced with burgeoning capital inflow and a rising trade surplus, the baht strengthened against the dollar, despite intense intervention from the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the currency market. Unable to absorb the flood of cash pouring into the country, officials eventually pulled the break and imposed capital control. This, in turn, contributed to a severe downturn in investor confidence, from which the country is still recovering. Clearly, the main problem facing Thailand, like Indonesia now, was how to recycle an overwhelming payment surplus balance, not how to further bolster \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Most importantly, Asia requires genuine exchange rate coordination to manage the appreciation of its currencies against the dollar. Only a coordinated solution is possible whereby all central banks agree to let their currencies creep upward.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080508e4580000k\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
