\par\par \b \uc2 The politicking behind \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2 's planned sale\b0\par\par\uc2 Vincent Lingga , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 932 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 May 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 3\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 It is unlikely anything will come of the media hype over the past few weeks about the keen competition between four global steel giants to acquire up to a 40 percent stake in state-owned \uc2 PT Krakatau Steel\uc2 , Indonesia's largest steel producer with annual capacity of 2.5 million tons.\par \par \uc2 The headlines began after global steel giants ArcelorMittal, \uc2 Tata Steel\uc2  and Essar, all from India, and \uc2 BlueScope Steel\uc2  of Australia separately notified Indonesia's ministries of industry and state enterprises of their interest in acquiring up to 40 percent of \uc2 Krakatau Steel.\par \par \uc2 But even before serious negotiations began and the potential investors submitted their business plans, politicking and controversy have been heating up.\par \par \uc2 Vested interests within \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2 's boards of directors and commissioners and trade union immediately came out in opposition to the sales plan, arguing the steel company was too strategic for the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests to be sold to foreigners.\par \par \uc2 The legal aspects of the privatization of state companies are entirely under the jurisdiction of the state enterprises minister, and such a transaction can be conducted only with prior permits from the inter-ministerial Privatization Commission and parliament.\par \par \uc2 But the potential investors did nothing wrong in also consulting the ministry of industry, which is fully in charge of the regulatory and \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  framework of the steel industry, before submitting their business plans to Djalil.\par \par \uc2 As with the controversy over previous privatizations of state companies, the vested interests, including politicians in the parliament, would likely gang up in flaunting national interests as the main reason for their opposition, whipping up xenophobia.\par \par \uc2 But what they really want is to maintain state companies as their cash cows.\par \par \uc2 The defense ministry also joined the fray, trying to shoot down the privatization idea by asserting that \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2  is strategic to the country's defense industry.\par \par \uc2 True, steel is a strategic commodity. But what is strategic about \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2  if it remains grossly inefficient and small.\par \par \uc2 Ten years ago, the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  blocked an attempt by Lakshmi Mittal, ArcelorMittal's chief executive officer, to buy a stake in \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2 , even after then minister of state enterprises Tanri Abeng, impatient with the inefficiency of the state company, consented to the deal.\par \par \uc2 Strategic sales should theoretically be the best way for \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2  to improve its competitiveness and expand its production capacity, because it needs not only fresh capital but, most importantly, a strategic partner that can provide the capital, technology and managerial expertise.\par \par \uc2 Economies of scale and high technology are key to the market competitiveness of a steel producer. Without a synergy with a strategic partner, \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2  will remain tiny as it has been since its establishment over 30 years ago.\par \par \uc2 An initial \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  offering on the Indonesian Stock Exchange -- the option initially planned for \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2 's privatization this year -- is not favorable now, given the bearish market sentiment caused by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the global financial market and a weakening global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 It is not \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2  itself that has attracted the four steel giants but the huge potential Indonesia offers as a major production base for steel. The company itself, like most other state firms not traded on the stock exchange, is inefficient, burdened with excess baggage from decades of mismanagement during Soeharto's authoritarian rule and highly vulnerable to corruption by the management and "poaching" by senior officials and politicians.\par \par \uc2 The four potential investors have a long-term horizon, looking into the future of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The country now needs more than 6 million tons of steel, of which 2 million tons have to be imported, and the domestic market will certainly grow steadily as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  expands.\par \par \uc2 But strategic sales of state companies have always been difficult and vulnerable to "political turbulence" because the government has yet to develop standard operational procedures, the step-by-step process to secure transparency and accountability and to close any loopholes that could be exploited by corrupt officials.\par \par \uc2 Given the slippery political road ahead, here is some free advice for the potential investors: tread very carefully at every step of the long, slippery process, otherwise you may be caught in an imbroglio engineered by the vested interest groups within \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2 , parliament or other ministries.\par \par \uc2 Look what happened to Mexico's \uc2 Cemex\uc2  cement group, which quit sate-owned \uc2 PT Semen Gresik\uc2  last year after almost 10 years of legal and political harassment, or Singapore's \uc2 Temasek\uc2 , which is now trapped in a messy litigation for its investments in state-controlled \uc2 PT Indosat\uc2  and PT Telkomsel.\par \par \uc2 This is just to mention a few of the foreign investors who have suffered from attacks by vested interests eager to maintain state companies as cash cows.\par \par \uc2 Minister Djalil is well advised to realize that privatization, if well managed with high standards of transparency and accountability, is greatly effective in improving macroeconomic efficiency through the promotion of a more competitive market and more efficient and consequently more profitable enterprises, bringing in larger \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue for the state.\par \par \uc2 It is simply much better to put state firms in the hands of private investors who can develop the assets into profitable businesses, which create more jobs and pay more \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , rather than maintaining them as state assets that are easily plundered by senior officials and politicians.\par \par \uc2 More efficient and competitive state companies, especially those operating in upstream industries like \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2 , have multiplier impacts on downstream industries.\par \par \uc2 The great concern about a minority foreign shareholder in \uc2 Krakatau Steel\uc2  is therefore rather strange.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080514e45e0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 BI needs risk management implementation\b0\par\par\uc2 595 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 May 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The biggest challenge of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Indonesia (BI) Boediono is to cope with inflation rate and to implement risk management in the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 BNI economist Ryan Kiryanto said there are at least six challenges for Boediono as the new appointed BI Governor. First, he should control the inflation on the single digit level through monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Second, he should improve a more harmonious coordination between the government and \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc