\par\par \b \uc2 Oil dilemma: The ramifications of fuel price hikes\b0\par\par\uc2 Purbaya Yudhi Sadewa , Analyst   \par \uc2 755 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 May 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 In response to rises in global crude oil prices, the government has announced it will soon increase fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This has fueled concerns inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will follow suit, leading to weaker purchasing power, and slower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion.\par \par \uc2 However, careful analysis of the situation suggests there will not be significant reduction in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rate in the immediate future.\par \par \uc2 In 2007, the average price of WTI -- a global benchmark for oil prices -- was US$72.3 per barrel, while ICP (Indonesian Crude Price) averaged $69.9 per barrel.\par \par \uc2 In early 2008, oil prices started to rise, before falling slightly in late January, and climbing sharply again in mid-February 2008. In May 2008, WTI surpassed $120 per barrel.\par \par \uc2 In the January-May period, WTI averaged $104.1 per barrel, with ICP at $98.7 per barrel.\par \par \uc2 The sharp increases have threatened the sustainability of the 2008 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which assumes ICP to be $95 per barrel (on average, ICP is $5 below WTI).\par \par \uc2 The government has subsequently had to allocate around Rp 126.7 trillion ($13.6 billion) for fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 As the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  (currently planned at around 2.1 percent of GDP) has continued to increase, the Indonesian bond and equity markets have grown nervous.\par \par \uc2 Fortunately, there is some \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  flexibility as the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  has cleared room for the government to raise fuel prices should oil exceed $100 per barrel. In doing so, they have significantly reduced the threat to the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 With little hope global prices will fall below $100 per barrel, the government announced it would raise fuel prices in early June in an effort to prevent fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  from ballooning.\par \par \uc2 The finance minister has suggested the government is likely to raise subsidized fuel prices in June by an average of almost 30 percent.\par \par \uc2 The planned increases suggest the government assumes ICP will stay at around $110 per barrel (and WTI at $115 per barrel) during the May to December 2008 period.\par \par \uc2 With the price increases, the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be capped according to the already approved 2008 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , thus eliminating the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the impact of high global oil prices on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The announcement has already helped restore investor confidence in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The JCI (Jakarta Composite Index) has risen sharply since the government's announcement, and Indonesian bonds have also gained.\par \par \uc2 So, what of the impacts on inflation, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth?\par \par \uc2 According to our calculations, a 10 percent rise in the price of subsidized fuel would increase inflation by 0.7 percent. Thus, a 30 percent increase in fuel prices in June would increase inflation 2.1 percent.\par \par \uc2 The year-on-year inflation rate could rise to 11.3 percent in June, while this year's rate is expected to reach 10.66 percent.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  will likely increase its benchmark rate, although we do not believe the rise will reach a level that would hurt the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . By the year's end, we expect the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to have increased its BI rate to 9.0 percent, with little impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 As long as the BI rate holds below 10 percent, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should continue to expand healthily.\par \par \uc2 In the 2003-2006 period, Danareksa's Coincident \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index or CEI (an index that tracks current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions) rose when the BI rate was below 10 percent. A slight increase in the BI rate did not affect CEI's gain, suggesting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continued to expand.\par \par \uc2 However, as soon as the BI rate hit 10 percent, CEI held firm. When the BI rate moved beyond 10 percent, CEI started to fall, suggesting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  started to contract.\par \par \uc2 The behavior of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has not changed significantly over the last five years. As such, CEI is likely to continue increasing (i.e. the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  shall expand) as long as the BI rate remains below 10 percent.\par \par \uc2 In March 2005, the government increased fuel prices by 30 percent on average, and by 126 percent in October 2005. Our calculations show every 10 percent rise in fuel prices will reduce GDP growth by 0.02 percent.\par \par \uc2 The 30 percent planned fuel price increases are therefore likely to reduce GDP growth by 0.06 percent. Thus, we expect the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow 6.28 percent in 2008, or slightly less than our original forecast of 6.34 percent.\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at \uc2 Danareksa Sekuritas.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080522e45m00012\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
