\par\par \b \uc2 Reform movement led to democracy: former protester\b0\par\par\uc2 Primastuti Handayani , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 641 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 May 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 27\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 It was late at night but students at the then-Jakarta Teachers Training Institute (IKIP) were busy making a giant banner at a small market behind their campus. When the morning came, IKIP Jakarta rector Sucipto and the university's post-graduate study director Jujun Suriasumantri told the under- and post-graduate students to be ready for a rally in front of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  building in Senayan, Central Jakarta.\par \par \uc2 The move was taken after the military shot dead four Trisakti University students during a protest inside the campus compound on May 12, 1998. The tra-gedy triggered nationwide protests and riots.\par \par \uc2 IKIP Jakarta post-graduate students forum chairman James Tangkudung recalled these hectic and tense moments.\par \par \uc2 "It was impossible to do nothing after the Trisakti shootings. All students in Jakarta -without agreement - simultaneously staged protest rallies. And we all marched to the House building," said James, now a professor of sports medicine at Jakarta State University (the new name of IKIP Jakarta).\par \par \uc2 "We were the first at the House's gates but we had prepared everything. Not only the banner. We had an ambulance with us, filled with food, water and medicine.\par \par \uc2 "The soldiers pointed their guns at Pak Sucipto, Pak Jujun and me. We told them that we would like to meet the lawmakers and suddenly someone shouted that we had an appointment with (lawmaker) Pak Hari Sabarno," he said.\par \par \uc2 The students were allowed to enter the House compound and began to hang the banners. Two hours later, students from the University of Indonesia and other universities and organizations joined in. They camped at the House for three days before lawmakers called on president Soeharto to step down. Soeharto eventually did so on May 21.\par \par \uc2 James, who is now an assistant to the state minister for youth and sports affairs, praised the reform movement for making a change in Indonesia, especially in terms of democracy and politics.\par \par \uc2 "Now, we have direct elections, be they at the presidential or regional level. The regional direct elections have been going well although there are still some disputes in several areas due to the outcome of the elections.\par \par \uc2 "We have also made progress in handling conflicts like what the government did in Aceh, Papua, Maluku and Poso.\par \par \uc2 "The people also have the freedom of speech, which is one of the demands in the reform movement," he said.\par \par \uc2 However, James said that Indonesia has also been facing lots of problems in the past five years, especially with the devastating tsunami that hit Aceh on Dec. 26, 2004.\par \par \uc2 "We are facing natural disasters and environmental destruction. Those are the unavoidable things. Whoever the president is, it will not be easy to lead Indonesia in such a situation," said James, who joined the humanitarian effort after the Aceh tsunami.\par \par \uc2 Ten years after the reform movement, James sees that some Indonesians are still not prepared for such a big change.are fighting against corruption, which remains rampant today although the government has taken some stern measures to curb it. The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is also \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  with the rumors of fuel price hikes.\par \par \uc2 "The \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  should remain calm. If they are not satisfied with the incumbent government, then don't vote for them in the next election. We should give the government a chance to work," he said.\par \par \uc2 He also said that the students today did not face a common enemy like 10 years ago. "Even if they want to stage protests, they don't know who their enemy is. The situation is not clear.\par \par \uc2 "Back then, we also received support from the middle class. Now it doesn't happen. There are also infiltrations by political parties into campuses for the sake of the parties. They don't have the same goals as we did."\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080522e45m0001m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
