\par\par \b \uc2 Small fuel price hike will trigger new  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 Vincent Lingga , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 759 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 May 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono eased market concerns about the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability when, after several months of indecision, he made up his mind earlier this month about the urgent need to raise fuel prices.\par \par \uc2 The financial market was buoyed by this, even though questions on the amount of the rise and the date it would take effect were left unanswered.\par \par \uc2 The government on Wednesday removed an element of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  within the fuel reform plan by fixing the size of the upcoming price increase at 28.70 percent but, in keeping with Yudhoyono's characteristic indecisiveness, still did not address the question of "when".\par \par \uc2 Yet more worrisome is the size of the price hike seems so small that, even on the basis of the prevailing international prices (which will likely continue to increase), there will still be a disparity of 40 percent or more with market prices.\par \par \uc2 This is still quite a lucrative margin for smugglers to take advantage of. Such a big difference leaves great temptation for misuse by industrial users.\par \par \uc2 Since international oil prices will likely continue their upward trend and the domestic-to-world price ratio will increase steadily, this otherwise bold measure will be made less credible. It will instead cause a new element of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the market perceives the measure as merely temporary.\par \par \uc2 Despite government assurances there will not be any further price increases this year, the market is still asking when the next one will occur, because the proposed 28.70 percent rise would not even bring domestic prices close to 70 percent of international levels like the October 2005 fuel price rise did.\par \par \uc2 The market would likely reject the price adjustment as inadequate in making a big positive impact on the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position. The new fuel prices will neither remove the incentives for smuggling overseas, nor provide the right market signal for fuel conservation, efficiency and investment in alternative, renewable energy sources.\par \par \uc2 We find it hard to understand why the government did not follow up on its bold move in 2005 when it increased fuel prices by 30 percent in March and again by 125 percent in October.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  underwent a virtuous circle within one week following the fuel reform in October 2005: the stock market rose, the rupiah strengthened and consequently reduced inflationary pressures. The market even shrugged off the impact of another terrorist bomb attack in Bali which took place almost on the same day the government more than doubled fuel prices.\par \par \uc2 Any move to raise fuel prices, irrespective of the amount, will always trigger street demonstrations. Anyway, almost any issue will give rise to protests under our present democratic system. Any measure to increase energy prices will always fuel inflationary pressures. But with good coordination between \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary authorities, and well managed cash transfers and other poverty programs for the poor the inflationary impact can be contained, the panic reaction minimized and poor families protected from an adverse impact.\par \par \uc2 But raising fuel prices in little increments would only prolong the pains of the reform, planting a "new time bomb" which would likely explode six months or one year from now.\par \par \uc2 Thus the fuel price \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  the government will announce within the next few days should be supplemented with an additional fixed schedule for a gradual phasing out of fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  for private cars until the prices are automatically floated on Mid Oil Platts Singapore (MOPS) quotations and the rupiah's exchange rate, such as those already imposed on industrial users.\par \par \uc2 Such flotation will allow for an automatic monthly price adjustment, thereby providing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  predictability for the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from shocking inflationary pressures and sparing the government the wasteful political bickering with the parliament that occurs each time international oil prices fluctuate wildly.\par \par \uc2 It's a technical matter how such a fuel price flotation should be implemented to prevent shocking inflationary pressures. After all, we have been on that road once before in 2002.\par \par \uc2 We don't foresee any major problems in managing fuel distribution under the two-tier price scheme because state-owned oil company \uc2 Pertamina\uc2 , the monopoly of subsidized fuels, has built up enough expertise to minimize misuse.\par \par \uc2 What is most important is floating domestic fuel prices on international levels will free the government from enslavement to the wildly volatile international oil market, remove the fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  "time bomb" from its \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  management and forces fuel efficiency and conservation and encourages investment in alternative renewable energy.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080523e45n00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
