\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Economy \highlight\uc2  to weather fuel price hikes: IMF\b0\par\par\uc2 Aditya Suharmoko , The Jakarta Post, Jakarta   \par \uc2 574 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 May 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will remain stable throughout the year with strong investment and exports set to compensate for a slight dip in private consumption despite increases in fuel prices, the International Monetary Fund says.\par \par \uc2 IMF's senior resident representative in Indonesia, Stephen Schwartz, told a discussion Thursday the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  this year would grow 6.1 percent, as "the stronger-than-expected momentum from the first quarter offsets the expected near-term impact of the recent fuel prices increase".\par \par \uc2 The forecast, made after a meeting with the government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , is higher than the government's target of 6 percent growth, and the BI's target of less than 6.1 percent, but is unchanged from IMF's previous forecast dated October 2007.\par \par \uc2 "The outlook is positive, but it is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  because of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook," Schwartz said.\par \par \uc2 Milan Zavadjil, IMF's assistant director in its Asia and Pacific department, said, "We expect (\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) growth to sort of pick up gradually, but it depends on the world's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."\par \par \uc2 The world's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  may face a prolonged slowdown due in part to consistent rises in global oil and commodity prices, in addition to a slowing U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  hit hard by subprime credit woes.\par \par \uc2 The government last week raised subsidized fuel prices -- Premium gasoline, diesel and kerosene -- by an average of 28.7 percent on fears global oil prices would continue to increase fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidy\b0 \highlight\uc2  costs and stretch the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Zavadjil and Schwartz said the fuel price increase might slightly slow private consumption over the coming months due to a decrease in people's purchasing power, but that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would continue to grow as expected on consistently strong investment and exports.\par \par \uc2 Private consumption accounts for 60 percent of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while investment and exports each contribute 20 percent.\par \par \uc2 In the first quarter of 2008, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew 6.3 percent on robust growth in private consumption, investment and exports, as reported by the Central Statistics Agency.\par \par \uc2 Investment grew 2.9 percent from in the same period last year, private consumption by 3.2 percent and exports by 7.1 percent.\par \par \uc2 However, the IMF said the government and BI must control inflationary pressures, which they cited as the year's most pressing challenge, even more so than fuel price increases.\par \par \uc2 The government predicted full-year inflation would reach 11.2 percent, while BI estimated it to hit almost 12 percent.\par \par \uc2 To control inflation, Zavadjil said BI would likely raise its interest rate. "BI has signaled its intention to tighten (its rate) further as needed to bring inflation back from a declining trend."\par \par \uc2 The IMF said the financial sector had stood firm amid turmoil in the global credit market.\par \par \uc2 "Financial soundness indicators have improved, with profitability across the banking industry increasing and non-performing loans continuing to decline amid strong private sector credit growth.\par \par \uc2 "BI needs to look closely at how banks are managing their risks, and banks need to ensure their lending quality," Zavadjil said.\par \par \uc2 BI has said it will monitor lending growth, which is currently growing at a rate of 29 percent, higher than BI's prediction of between 22 and 24 percent for this year.\par \par \uc2 Should the government and BI manage to address the problems, the IMF predicted the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would grow 6.3 percent in 2009, with inflation slowing to 7.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080530e45u0001k\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
