\par\par \b \uc2 Inflation extends credit worries for banking industry\b0\par\par\uc2 Teguh Hartanto , Consultant   \par \uc2 664 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 July 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Cheap loans are becoming a thing of the past. Since the beginning of the year, the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) rate has increased 75 basis points to its current level of 8.75 percent, and it is likely to rise further as the government looks to curb inflation.\par \par \uc2 In line with inflationary pressure, we are seeing a contraction of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth squeezing consumer purchasing power.\par \par \uc2 Having said that, the pick up in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  has made consumers and corporations nervous about their ability to secure cheap credit facilities. Judging from past experience, lenders may be inclined to tighten their credit control to prevent ballooning non-performing loans.\par \par \uc2 Still, we do not foresee a credit crisis in the making, as we expect BI to be able to lower inflation to single digits and push up \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth above 6 percent next year.\par \par \uc2 In general, these rising purchase price multiples and the falling ratio of cash that consumers and companies have on hand to cover expenses will make it harder for them to repay their loans and put pressure on default rates in the wake of this credit crisis.\par \par \uc2 However, we believe the magnitude will not be as immense as that in the United States, where billions of dollars were lost through bad loans and blundered investments.\par \par \uc2 During the "mini crisis" in 2005, non-performing loans in the domestic banking sector touched 8.5 percent before declining consistently.\par \par \uc2 It is worth noting, however, that the high non-performing loans were mostly in the form of inherited corporate loans triggered by state-owned banks (i.e. \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2  and \uc2 Bank Negara Indonesia\uc2 ). That said, focus on loan quality has nowadays discouraged banks from aggressively channeling their excess funds.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, lower \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  purchasing power should pave the way for slower loan consumption, while over the past few years wages have not kept pace with inflation.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian banks will therefore focus their credit expansion on certain promising market segments, i.e. resources, agribusiness and infrastructure related industries.\par \par \uc2 The fear that banks will be not be able to generate future earnings growth nor curb the potential ballooning of non-performing loans has led to the recent more-than 20-percent plunge in share prices of many domestically-listed finance-related companies.\par \par \uc2 While these rather steep corrections in share prices might arguably give an exaggerated account of the situation given that Indonesian banks are not exposed to the sub-prime woes as the U.S. banks are, a global de-rating in the valuations of financial stocks in general has dragged down the overall sentiment of their Indonesian counterparts in our view.\par \par \uc2 And until the fear of global financial risks subsides, we can probably expect the impact on the American market to continue to spread to Indonesian banks.\par \par \uc2 Concerns linger as investors continue to weigh the possibility of a potential increase in the SBI rate to 9.50 percent by the end of 2008.\par \par \uc2 Most banks have upwardly adjusted their teaser rate as many predict inflation pressure could prompt the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to further raise its benchmark rate later in the year.\par \par \uc2 An interview with some prominent banks showed that they felt a 200 to 300 basis points increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would not stretch their comfort zone in channeling loans.\par \par \uc2 At this stage, we do not expect significant increases in non-performing loans because the sector can draw from the lessons learned during the Asian financial crisis of 1998.\par \par \uc2 Although the outlook for the banking sector is currently far from rosy, we believe the steep alterations in the prices of bank shares have already largely taken into account the concerns on the current high inflation environment.\par \par \uc2 Depending on oil price movement, the predicted low inflation rate and strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year should abate pessimism within the sector.\par \par \uc2 The best way to safeguard against \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is to expect the unexpected and plan for the worst, while still hoping for the best.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080709e4790001b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
