\par\par \b \uc2 Climate change controversy: Its impacts and opportunities\b0\par\par\uc2 Michael Richardson , Singapore   \par \uc2 866 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 July 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 We know that the world is gradually warming. Most scientists agree this is due to man's activities, particularly the burning of fossil fuels like coal, oil and natural gas, and the release of huge amounts of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gas emissions into the atmosphere.\par \par \uc2 However, there is debate over the rate of climate change and some \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about its impact. Even so, the World Health Organization is worried that climate change endangers human health in fundamental ways.\par \par \uc2 While the warming of the planet may be gradual, the effects of extreme weather induced by climate change -- more storms, floods, droughts and heatwaves -- will be acute and immediate.\par \par \uc2 But the consequences won't be evenly distributed. Scientists predict that developing countries, particularly those with big populations in Asia and Africa, and small, low-lying island states such as those in the Pacific and Indian oceans, will be first and hardest hit.\par \par \uc2 The WHO is concerned that climate change will further degrade the basic determinants of health: Water, air, food, shelter and freedom from disease. It has identified five major health consequences of climate change.\par \par \uc2 First, farming and food production are extremely sensitive to climate variation. Rising temperatures, bigger fluctuations in rainfall, and more frequent droughts and floods are likely to reduce crop yields in many areas.\par \par \uc2 At a time of rising food prices, this is an added challenge to global food security. It also makes people more susceptible to illness.\par \par \uc2 Water scarcity already affects four out of every ten people. Shifting rainfall patterns, increased rates of evaporation and melting of glaciers, combined with population and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, are expected to raise the number of people living in water-short regions to between three and six billion by 2050, from about 1.5 billion in 1990.\par \par \uc2 Increases in malnutrition are projected to be especially severe in countries like China and India where large numbers of people depend on rain-fed subsistence farming.\par \par \uc2 Malnutrition, much of it caused by periodic drought, is already responsible for an estimated 3.5 million deaths each year.\par \par \uc2 Second, more frequent extreme weather will intensify the spread of disease, as well as cause more deaths and injuries from storms and floods. Approximately 600,000 deaths occurred worldwide from weather-related natural disasters in the 1990s, nearly all in developing nations.\par \par \uc2 Flooding in poor countries is often followed by outbreaks of cholera and other diseases when water and sanitation services, often inadequate in the first place, are damaged or destroyed.\par \par \uc2 Storms and floods, like those that struck Myanmar and southern China recently, are already among the most frequent and deadly forms of natural disasters.\par \par \uc2 Third, both scarcity of water, which is essential for hygiene, and excess water from more frequent torrential rain, will worsen diarrhoeal disease spread through contaminated food and water. Diarrhoeal disease already accounts for approximately 1.8 million deaths each year.\par \par \uc2 Fourth, heatwaves -- especially in cities, which are natural heat traps -- can raise death and illness rates from heart and respiratory illness. This will be a growing problem as more and more people settle in urban centers.\par \par \uc2 Recent studies suggest that the heatwave in Europe in the summer of 2003 caused an estimated 70,000 more deaths than the equivalent periods in previous years.\par \par \uc2 Higher temperatures affect levels and seasonal patterns of soot, dust and natural airborne particles, such as plant pollen, which can trigger asthma. About 300 million people suffer from this condition and 255,000 people died of it in 2005, according to the WHO.\par \par \uc2 It says that asthma deaths are expected to rise by almost 20 per cent in the next 10 years if climate change continues unabated.\par \par \uc2 Fifth, global warming is expected to spread diseases like malaria, and dengue and Chikungunya fever, that are transmitted by mosquitoes or other insects. Malaria kills almost one million people each year, mainly in Africa and Asia. The WHO estimates that there may be 50 million cases of dengue infection annually, chiefly in the tropics. Some 500,000 case require hospitalization and about 12,500 cases are fatal.\par \par \uc2 Warmer temperatures, higher humidity and more places where water can collect for mosquitoes to breed, such as in the tropics, favors malaria, dengue and Chikungunya transmission. Cooler countries and places, associated with higher altitudes and latitudes, have been free of these mosquito-borne diseases. But this is expected to change as temperatures rise around the world.\par \par \uc2 The WHO and other United Nations agencies are intensifying research into the likely impact of climate change on human health.\par \par \uc2 The aim is to find ways to protect health in a hotter world with more extreme weather. One safeguard is to strengthen basic \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  health services.\par \par \uc2 In Asia, this helped cut the number of reported dengue fever cases to under 345,000 cases in 2005, from over 760,000 in 1990.\par \par \uc2 But it will be difficult to sustain this progress if the demands on government resources multiply as climate change exacerbates other challenges to global stability and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 The writer, a former Asia editor of the International Herald Tribune , is an energy and security specialist at the Institute of South East Asian Studies in Singapore.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080710e47a0000h\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 ' \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Growth in 2009 to Remain Strong'\b0\par\par\uc2 420 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 July 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The Association of Indonesian Young Businesspersons (Hipmi) is optimistic Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2009 will remain strong at 6%-6.4% of the GDP despite the looming threat of high inflation.\par \par \uc2 Chairperson of the Hipmi Sandiaga Uno believed Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  next year would increase just as projected in the 2009 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  draft.\par \par \uc2 However, he continued, inflation would likely remain high and be potential to undermine business competitiveness. "Around 50% of the Hipmi members are optimistic the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target for 2009 will be achieved," he said to Bisnis yesterday.\par \par \uc2 The National Development Planning Agency (Bappenas) previously estimated Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2009 would grow by 6.4%.\par \par \uc2 Bambang Widianto, advisory staff to the State Minister/Head of the Bappenas for Human Resources and Poverty, viewed Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth next year would remain high.\par \par \uc2 For this year, the government forecasted the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the first semester of 2008 would grow by 6.2%.\par \par \uc2 Minister of Finance Sri Mulyani Indrawati recently explained Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth would remain strong this year, thanks to the increase in household consumption by 5.3%.\par \par \uc2 She analyzed despite the fuel price hikes in May 2008 the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the first semester of this year would relatively be good.\par \par \uc2 "The high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6.3% in the first quarter and the projected \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6.1% in the first semester lead us to forecast the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the first semester will reach 6.2%," she exposed.\par \par \uc2 The strong Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was reflected from strong household consumption, which represented 70% of the GDP and grew by 5.2%-5.3%.\par \par \uc2 According to Sandiaga, regional businesses would grow ahead and would dominate by representing 70% of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially in the agribusiness, infrastructure, and mining sectors.\par \par \uc2 Support SKB\par \par \uc2 He added the businesses would face greater challenges ahead in light of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  domestic and international \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turbulences. The challenges were also escalating with the issuance of the Joint Decision Letter of Five Ministers on the Shift of Working Days to Saturday and Sunday.\par \par \uc2 However, Sandiaga assured 30,000 young businesspersons grouped under the Hipmi would support the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as long as the government could provide certainty over the businesses' rights and responsibility.\par \par \uc2 He further emphasized the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should provide the employers with a strong legal foundation to prevent labors from asking for extra time pay.\par \par \uc2 "The Hipmi supports the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but the government should make clear arrangement about extra time pay." (Bisni