\par\par \b \uc2 Beware the siren's call of a  \highlight22\uc2 tax \highlight\uc2  on 'windfall' oil profits\b0\par\par\uc2 Christopher Lingle , Luxembourg   \par \uc2 902 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 August 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The government of Indonesia is considering a "windfall" profit \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on oil and gas companies. The presumption is that the additional funds might be used to ease the burden of higher energy prices.\par \par \uc2 It is true that international oil and gas companies have enjoyed rising profits due to increasing oil prices. With current global prices around US$140 per barrel, oil companies operating in Indonesia could earn up to a total of more than 40 trillion rupiah in profits this year.\par \par \uc2 It is calculated that a windfall profits \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 50 percent would increase revenues by more than 20 trillion. On the one hand, these estimates are likely to be overstated.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, it is no more reasonable to target oil company earnings than to \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  windfall earnings of rice farmers benefiting from global food price inflation.\par \par \uc2 The idea that a windfall \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on oil firms or an export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  will boost \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues without having much impact on the operations of the targeted firms is nonsense. This way of thinking contradicts a basic law of economics: The importance of incentives.\par \par \uc2 Incentives are derived from the rule structure within which individuals or corporations make decisions. Changing the rules that define payments and penalties of behavior will lead to different decisions.\par \par \uc2 Raising \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  burdens or altering the structure of \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  will change the behavior of oil firms that will have unintended consequences. Rising oil prices encourage companies to invest more to find new \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  and increase production from existing fields.\par \par \uc2 Higher \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on oil company revenues will reduce their willingness and ability to seek and produce more oil. As such, a windfall profits \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  will reduce capital available for investment in future energy production and less government revenues in the future.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, it may also lead to consumers facing higher prices. Since \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  raise the overhead cost of doing businesses, they tend to try to pass them on to consumers.\par \par \uc2 It is useful to consider the experience of the U.S. on imposing a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on windfall profits in the 1980s. The Carter administration offered a compromise to the U.S. to lift ceilings on oil prices in 1984. The result was a complex \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  system that was eventually discarded in 1988, two-and-a-half years before an automatically expiration date.\par \par \uc2 A 2006 report by the Congressional Research Service revealed that the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  raised less than the quarter of a trillion dollars estimated by it supporters, yielding only $40 billion. However, it was seen to have contributed to a decline in domestic oil production of from 3 percent up to 6 percent and an increase in oil imports by perhaps as much as 15 percent.\par \par \uc2 Whatever the political motives, there is no legal basis for imposing a windfall profits \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on oil companies operating in Indonesia. Existing regulations require that existing working contracts between the government and companies be revised before an extra \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  are imposed, including on windfall profits. This is good news since imposing such an additional \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  might drive investors away while also reducing incentives for oil companies to increase domestic production.\par \par \uc2 In all events, the notion of a "windfall" profit is highly subjective since there is no clear difference from ordinary profit. While there is no absolute number or return on equity or on sales to determine whatconstitutes reasonable earnings, it seems to matter only which sector of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is earning it.\par \par \uc2 As mentioned above, rice farmers and palm oil producers are surely earning windfalls from rapidly rising prices of their output. Yet there are no suggestions for a special \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on their earnings nor have these groups been accused of profiteering.\par \par \uc2 For their part, oil-producing firms do not set their prices since the price of a barrel of oil comes from international markets through sales between buyers and sellers. In all events, it would constitute a penalty for the fact that oil prices skyrocketed due to booming demand from in China and India and tensions in the Middle East.\par \par \uc2 Better moves would be to set policies that improve cost recovery and encourage exports as well as simplifying investment procedures and ending the production \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . As it is, foreign investment is lagging due to an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  regulatory environment and a dubious respect for contracts.\par \par \uc2 Up to now, the record of government interferences in Indonesia's energy markets is pretty dismal. \b \highlight22\uc2 Subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  created massive distortions and inept handling of exploration contracts and a poor investment environment kept billions of barrels of oil undiscovered and untapped.\par \par \uc2 While taxing "windfall" profits earned by businesses may generate political rewards, it fails to protect consumers since only people pay \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Taxing businesses imposes a burden on workers that may earn less or encounter job losses. And consumers are likely to be hit with higher prices while shareholders may see stock prices decline.\par \par \uc2 Imposing \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  based on emotional or political impulses rather than using \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  logic will bring long-term costs that overwhelm any short-term benefits. Increased adherence to the rule of law and to the sanctity of contracts are better ways to enhance Indonesia's long-term energy supplies.\par \par \uc2 The writer is Research Scholar at the Centre for Civil Society in New Delhi and Visiting Professor of Economics at Universidad Francisco Marroquin in Guatemala. He can be reached at CLingle@ufm.edu\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080812e48c0000m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
