\par\par \b \uc2 The election-year  \highlight22\uc2 budget \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 An election year usually sees a greatly expansive \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the incumbent government works hard to attract voters by distributing political goodies.   \par \uc2 865 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 August 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 However, with inflation estimated at around 11 percent throughout this year, the 2009 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , proposed to parliament last week by President Soesilo Bambang Yudhoyono, represents (in real terms) a mere 2.4 percent increase in total \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to Rp 1,122 trillion (US$123 billion).\par \par \uc2 Certainly not an expansive \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , nor a pump priming one, in view of the parliamentary and presidential elections next year.\par \par \uc2 With more than 20 percent (or Rp 227 trillion) of the total \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocated to \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  (around 71 percent of this for fuel and electricity alone) and with a 15 percent pay rise for civil servants, we cannot help but see the draft \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as supporting SBY's aim to be reelected.\par \par \uc2 For the first time in the nation's history, the government plans to allocate 20 percent of its total \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to education (thus fulfilling a stipulation of the Constitution), by increasing the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for this sector to Rp 224 trillion.\par \par \uc2 This should be a welcome development because human resources have long been one of the least developed sectors in Indonesia, blamed for an acute shortage of highly trained and skilled workers.\par \par \uc2 Yet we are a little apprehensive of how the government will go about distributing the additional \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  across the educational sector, aiming for a harmonious balance between building institutional capacity and physical infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 The appropriation of Rp 142.8 trillion for poverty alleviation in rural and urban areas is a good decision given that more than 15 percent of our population of 130 million still live below the poverty line. But again, our biggest concern is the government's capacity in \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 -execution.\par \par \uc2 Despite the 13.40 percent nominal increase planned in total \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the 2009 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will check the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at only 1.9 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) -- slightly less than an estimate of 2.1 percent made earlier this year.\par \par \uc2 The government made this all possible by simply tinkering with the assumed oil price. By reducing the assumed average price of oil for the whole of next year to $100/barrel (as against the actual price of $140 in the first semester of this year) the government expects to slash fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to Rp 101.4 trillion from an estimated Rp 180.3 trillion this year. Despite a decline in international oil prices over the past few weeks, this factor will be the biggest vulnerability of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, it is comforting to note that the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan includes a contingency allocation of Rp 6 trillion for additional \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- in case oil prices do reach $130/barrel.\par \par \uc2 Other basic assumptions adopted for the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  -- including 6.5 percent inflation, an exchange rate of Rp 9,100 for US$1, GDP growth of 6.2-6.5 percent and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's short-term interest rate of 8.5 percent -- all seem fairly realistic.\par \par \uc2 The projected decline in the ratio of total government debts against GDP to as low as 30 percent next year would help reduce the sovereign risk and consequently the government's borrowing costs amid the international credit crunch.\par \par \uc2 This would be greatly helpful in reducing the burden of the Indonesia's borrowing, as it will raise Rp 110 trillion ($12 billion) through rupiah and dollar bond issues to plug its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The government expects a 14.30 percent increase in total revenue, to Rp 1,022 trillion ($112 billion) -- not a highly optimistic target.\par \par \uc2 The surprisingly higher-than-estimated 6.4 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth (year-on-year) in the second quarter of 2007 could be a building block for consumer and business confidence in maintaining robust growth amid persistent \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the global financial market and weakening world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Consequently, we believe the estimated 20 percent increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipts is not too ambitious, especially in view of the lower \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates to be imposed under the new income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  law and a package of other taxpayer-friendly reform measures (including new procedures for filing \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns and \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  assessment). All these positive factors do not, however, allow for complacency on the part of the government.\par \par \uc2 The robust growth in the first semester was generated mainly by sky-high commodity prices (especially coal, palm oil, rubber and cocoa), but their prices seem to have peaked, and the only trend forward will likely be a decline, albeit gradual.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, non-\b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues which are budgeted at Rp 374 trillion (or 36.60 percent of total revenue) also depend largely on royalties from minerals and other natural resource commodities.\par \par \uc2 So, all in all the market will see the 2009 \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  plan as fairly realistic as it will continue in the direction of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  consolidation targeted by the current government -- unlike the current \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  which required significant changes before it could be approved.\par \par \uc2 At the end of the day, however, a \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  system is not self-contained. It doesn't operate in a vacuum, as it is influenced by external factors and entrenched patterns of inflation and structural imbalances between expectations and resources.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080818e48i0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
