\par\par \b \uc2 Crude palm oil prices: Reading into the roller-coaster ride\b0\par\par\uc2 Achmad Syafriel , Analyst   \par \uc2 761 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 August 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 13\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Crude palm oil (CPO) price movements have been nothing short of a roller-coaster ride. From a mid-June 2006 price of around US$400 per ton, it shot up 350 percent to $1,400 per ton in Rotterdam before plunging 37 percent to the current level.\par \par \uc2 The million dollar question is: Where are CPO prices headed.\par \par \uc2 In the U.S., Federal Reserve Chairman Bernanke signaled last week that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  expects the commodity rally to ease. Hence, the Fed is keeping its target for \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  "relatively low" because of "expectation that the prices of oil and other commodities would ultimately stabilize, in part as a result of slowing global growth," Bernanke was quoted as saying on Aug. 22 at the Kansas City Fed annual conference in Jackson Hole, Wyoming.\par \par \uc2 If this were to occur, it would do wonders for the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , bringing an end to what many earlier thought was an era of stagflation, marked by exorbitant oil and food prices amid an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown.\par \par \uc2 If oil prices were to reach $200 per barrel, for example, skyrocketing commodity prices could potentially damage the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and create a fragile political condition, particularly in a period leading up to the 2009 elections.\par \par \uc2 When oil prices reached nearly $150 per barrel, people around the world, including many Indonesians, were already complaining about expensive food prices as many commodities, including corn and CPO, had by then started being utilized as biofuels.\par \par \uc2 The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) even stated that a food crisis was unfolding globally, and estimated that the surging food prices may have added 50 million people to the starving population.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia should count its blessings that commodity prices have reversed and that the prediction has was incorrect.\par \par \uc2 On the Jakarta stock market, based on our calculation, investors, whether rightly or wrongly, are already pricing in CPO at $700 per ton for 2009 to value Indonesian CPO counters like Astra Agro, London Sumatra and Bakrie Sumatra Plantations.\par \par \uc2 This, however, is not far off from the current three-month CPO forward price of $768 per ton.\par \par \uc2 If commodity prices could stay down, inflation will come off allowing for \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  to come down in the second quarter of 2009. This would be good for sentiment on the stock market in general, although commodity-related counters could underperform.\par \par \uc2 However, over the longer-run, we believe massive population growth will continue to plague food sufficiency. The world's population has grown at a rate of 1.2 percent over the last 10 years.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, land availability for agriculture and plantations is diminishing every year. According to FAO, agriculture areas are declining by five to 10 square meters per hectare every year due to many factors.\par \par \uc2 More areas are being converted into houses or industries. Even though land availability is still abundant in Central Asia and Africa, the cost to build such areas for plantations is expensive. Fertilizers have become more expensive as the prices of raw materials, including natural gas, are also increasing.\par \par \uc2 To paint a bleaker picture of the connection between population growth and food availability, the U.S. Census Bureau International Database Division estimated based on its current growth trajectory that the world's population will reach nearly nine billion people in 2042.\par \par \uc2 In line with this situation, FAO estimates that the world's food supply will double in the same period.\par \par \uc2 In addition, as global climate changes are happening around the world, agriculture production will be affected. According to Indonesian oil palm plantation companies, it is becoming more difficult nowadays to make weather predictions needed for drawing up plans on planting and harvesting.\par \par \uc2 Taking the weather into account is crucial in making decisions on when to plant seeds, when to apply fertilizer and in what volume and estimating harvest time. In summary, climate change will have a more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  effect on food production as it is generally accepted that population growth increase or at least maintain food demand.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, it is imperative for countries around the world to make every effort to control their respective rates of population growth, place restrictions on the conversion of agriculture areas into houses/industries and continue to develop the agriculture sector by increasing planting and implementing better technology to increase productivity.\par \par \uc2 If not, the era of cheap food prices will not be revisited and we will continue to see record breaking soft commodity prices.\par \par \uc2 The writer is a research analyst at PT Bahana Securities\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080827e48r00011\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
