\par\par \b \uc2 The correction of oil prices\b0\par\par\uc2 The more than 30 percent drop in international oil prices from US$147 per barrel peak last July, to less than $100 last week, should comfort \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ), reduce inflationary pressures and lead to an easing of tighter monetary policies.   \par \uc2 755 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 September 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 However, weaker oil prices have triggered equally steep falls in commodity prices, especially coal, palm oil and food, causing the Indonesian (IDX) composite share index to fall by almost 11 percent last week. Compared to the IDX share index peak of 2,830 in early January, the stock exchange had lost more than 36 percent, or Rp 605 trillion (US$63.68 billion) off its market capitalization, as of last Friday.\par \par \uc2 The huge jumps in commodity prices since early 2007 are now reversing, partly because of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown which has spread from the United States to Europe and partly because of wider price adjustments.\par \par \uc2 Although the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over supply and demand may still add to price volatility, a big rebound in oil prices looks unlikely.\par \par \uc2 Overseas investors sold more Indonesian stocks than they bought over the past week, driving down the rupiah, as falling commodity prices led to fears of lower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 So is the fall in oil prices and its consequences, good for our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ? The answer is a qualified yes.\par \par \uc2 Skyrocketing rises in commodity prices since early last year seem to have been irrational and not entirely generated by the fundamentals of supply and demand. Speculative money, which fled the crumbling financial markets, undermined by the impact of the sub-prime mortgage crisis in the United States, probably had played a part in causing these huge jumps in commodity prices.\par \par \uc2 Sky-high oil prices set off equally huge rises in the prices of coal and other commodities used as alternative sources of energy, including palm oil and corn. This trend in turn drove up to the top of the charts the prices of other food commodities such as rice and wheat, setting off tremendous inflationary pressures and prompting the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to tighten up on credit.\par \par \uc2 But the significant decline in the prices of oil and other commodities since last month is good for the long-term stability of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , because it has helped remove the excessive fat or speculative component from these higher prices.\par \par \uc2 The weaker commodity prices and the recent credit controls imposed by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  certainly adversely affected the IDX because commodities (minerals and palm oil) accounted for almost 20 percent of the companies listed in the stock market, whilst financial services accounted for 23.50 percent.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is the world's largest exporter of both coal and palm oil.\par \par \uc2 Analysts say Indonesia, a largely natural-resource-based \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , is particularly exposed to growing fears of a deeper global downturn which could sap demand for commodities.\par \par \uc2 Most analysts saw the latest market trends as irrational, but so had been the sky-high prices of commodities over the past year. Rational investors should not have panicked because they should have known that these steep price rises since mid-1997 were simply not sustainable.\par \par \uc2 The surge in commodity prices in recent years was led by energy and food commodities. According to \uc2 Goldman Sachs\uc2 , aggregate prices of commodities jumped 76 percent during the year to June. Energy prices alone almost doubled.\par \par \uc2 The market correction of these unsustainable price rises should lead to a more stable market, anchored on the sound fundamentals of supply and demand.\par \par \uc2 We should not, however, expect the prices of commodities to fall again to their pre-2006 levels. The price falls over the past few weeks will bring commodity prices to a new, higher, more sustainable equilibrium.\par \par \uc2 It nevertheless remains an illusion to expect that the era of cheap oil will return.\par \par \uc2 It is simply irrational to expect oil prices to fall back as low as their 2006 level of $50 per barrel. Likewise, palm oil prices, which reached their peak of $1,400 per ton last March and fell to as low as $770 last week, will unlikely crash to as low as their 2006 levels of $350-400 per ton.\par \par \uc2 The message is that the latest trends in commodity prices should not cause government to act and behave as if "it is back to business as usual" with regard to the energy sector.\par \par \uc2 The government should keep pushing through its concerted efforts to diversify the sources of energy and increase energy efficiency and conservation, otherwise it will fall deeper into the trap of oil addiction.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080916e49g0000p\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
