\par\par \b \uc2 Easing the liquidity crunch\b0\par\par\uc2 708 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 September 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities' quick response to addressing the tight liquidity situation is a timely pump priming move amid the weakening global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and international financial crisis.\par \par \uc2 This could become another block for building confidence in the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook amid the great \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially its financial system.\par \par \uc2 The weakening global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has depressed international demand for Indonesian commodities, as evidenced by the steady decline in exports over the past three months. Moreover, inflation has been eroding people's purchasing power, depressing household consumption and reducing business confidence.\par \par \uc2 Yet more worrisome is that the prospects for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth have been undermined by crumbling infrastructure. The acute electricity shortage has forced rotating power blackouts in many areas and caused many businesses to reduce production.\par \par \uc2 Minister of Finance Sri Mulyani Indrawati confirmed last week that the government would speed up the disbursement of its development (investment) \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  through the banking system to fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities.\par \par \uc2 At least Rp 60 trillion (US$6.3 billion) will be injected into the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the next three months, on top of the operating \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . That should be quite a help not only to promoting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities, but also to mitigating negative impacts of the liquidity crunch within the banking system.\par \par \uc2 After \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  decided early this month to further tighten its monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by raising its benchmark interest rate by another 25 basis points to 9.25 percent -- as against the U.S. Fed funds rate of only 2 percent -- most commercial banks had been forced to jack up their deposit rates in a bid to raise more funds.\par \par \uc2 The liquidity crunch had been made worse because at a time when the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is tightening monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the disbursement of the government investment \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has slowed down, although government has continued to issue bonds at relatively high speed and volume.\par \par \uc2 The result, acknowledged by Sri Mulyani, has been the accumulation of around Rp 120 trillion in the government account at the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Since commercial banks have no access to this account, this huge sum is effectively idle money, that has been sucked out of the liquidity in the financial system.\par \par \uc2 Some analysts have even estimated total funds at the government account at the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  at between Rp 150 trillion and Rp 170 trillion, way larger than the average level in the same period last year.\par \par \uc2 At the same time there seems to have been no significant improvement in government capacity to spend its development (investment) \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  by implementing projects. This has been made worse by project officers and treasurers of government agencies who, because of excessive fear of being charged with corruption, have become inordinately careful in doing their jobs, to the point of bureaucratic inertia.\par \par \uc2 In addition improved \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection efforts have taken out more liquidity from the market than in the same period last year.\par \par \uc2 Many businesses have especially been squeezed further as several banks, strapped for liquidity, have even slowed down the disbursement of approved loans to their corporate borrowers, thereby slackening the pace of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities.\par \par \uc2 This is really bad because bank lending acts as a lubricant to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  system. That is because companies which borrow from a bank put some of the borrowed funds in their accounts at the bank from which they borrow. At the same time, a proportion of the borrowed funds are usually spent on suppliers or contractors who in turn usually park their funds at their bank.\par \par \uc2 Hence, the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of accelerating the implementation of its development projects could go a long way in easing the liquidity crunch in the market, at a time when the international financial market is bogged down in \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The 7.25 percentage point difference between our interest rate and the United States Fed funds rate is high enough to maintain portfolio investment in rupiah assets, if not to woo new capital inflows.\par \par \uc2 Of most importance is Sri Mulyani's assurance that she will remain in close consultation with the monetary authorities (\b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) in accelerating the disbursement of the investment \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This assurance is quite important especially at a time of global financial \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , because there is a direct relationship between inflation and exchange rates.\par \par \uc2