\par\par \b \uc2 How the U.S. crisis impacts Indonesia\b0\par\par\uc2 Umar Juoro , Jakarta   \par \uc2 936 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 September 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 The argument that the Asian economies, particularly the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , is decoupled from the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is not true. The Indonesian financial market is very much influenced by the U.S. financial crisis relevant to the subprime mortgage problem -- albeit indirectly.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian capital market has gone down around 35 percent since the beginning of the year, the rupiah value is depreciating and the bond price is under strong pressure, as portfolio investors are leaving Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 It is true that growth is relatively high at 6.4 percent for the second half of the year, but growth could be threatened by a further declining in commodity prices. It is fortunate that Indonesia's financial institutions do not have significant exposure to falling financial institutions in the United States.\par \par \uc2 Domestically, demand side is still quite strong, supported by high credit growth of more than 30 percent. However, most banks are experiencing tough times on the liquidity side -- some banks even offering a deposit rate of up to 13 percent, based on the deposited amount.\par \par \uc2 The growth of third party funds is only around 11 percent. With this situation the banks will soon need to slow down credit growth in line with the third party fund growth. In addition, high inflation, at least until the middle of 2009, is eroding purchasing power primarily for lower income groups which also will contribute to a reduction in consumer credit.\par \par \uc2 BI as the monetary authority cannot satisfy only one side of the business sector, especially the financial market's push for BI to be more aggressive in raising the interest rate in order to curb inflation and maintain a stable rupiah. BI seems only willing to increase the interest rate 25 bp, probably two more times in its monthly board meetings.\par \par \uc2 On other hand, BI has to take some measures to ease liquidity tightness in the banking sector. This seems contradictory to BI's main mission which is to check inflation, but this is the tenuous job BI has to undertake in \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  circumstances -- not to mention the pressure from domestic businesses and politicians for BI to not raise the interest rate.\par \par \uc2 The decline in commodity prices on one side hurts the capital market and it could reduce export revenue and thereby reduce growth. So far, despite the sharp decline in share prices of commodity companies, their balance sheets remain strong. If commodity prices decline sharply, this would also affect domestic banks as their exposure in corporate credit is primarily to commodity-related companies, mainly CPO and coal.\par \par \uc2 However, on the other side declining commodity prices could help to ease inflation pressures. Again the challenge for \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makers is how to reconcile conflicting conditions.\par \par \uc2 So far both monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities have done a good job in keeping the situation from getting even worse. Certainly there is criticism that BI is behind the curve in fighting inflation, and the Finance Ministry is not aggressive enough in propping up the sluggish bond market.\par \par \uc2 However, this needs to be kept in perspective given these \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions; externally there are financial institutions falling in the United States, and internally there is domestic pressure from various interest groups, and so the authorities have to be able to pursue a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that at least keeps things from getting worse while balancing different interests to facilitate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 We cannot expect there to be a major move from the authorities. BI would not intervene through a large injection into the currency market or to increase the interest rate aggressively in order to maintain the rupiah value at a certain level if external pressure continues. This is too risky. BI might allow the rupiah to slide down beyond 9500 to the U.S. dollar while avoiding high volatility.\par \par \uc2 Similarly, the Finance Ministry will not buy back bonds to stabilize the bond market. It has done that sufficiently before, and no further intervention in the bond market is required. As the demand for sovereign rupiah bonds is sharply declining, the Finance Ministry prefers to raise loans from multilateral agencies rather than by issuing bonds. Regardless, there is still a significant amount of \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  to be disbursed so there is no financial pressure.\par \par \uc2 For the time being, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition is very much determined by how the U.S. subprime mortgage crisis unfolds. The positive scenario is that by the end of the year things will be sorted out.\par \par \uc2 If this is the case the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would reap the benefit for its financial market in general. If things in the U.S. become worse with more financial institutions falling and if the measures taken by the U.S. authorities are not effective, the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could also be hard hit.\par \par \uc2 It seems there is not much to be done by the Indonesian monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities as our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is very open to the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Nevertheless, there is still an important domestic job which is to tackle the serious problem of fighting inflation. If monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities can manage inflation well, investors will not be too worried about the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Lower inflation means a stronger rupiah and a higher bond price. Lower inflation has to be achieved through a combination of monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by raising the interest rate and by solving the problem of supply, distribution, and transportation primarily for basic goods. Lower inflation also benefits the lower income group by restoring their purchasing power.\par \par \uc2 Umar Juoro is Chairman of CIDES (Center for Information and Development Studies), and Senior Fellow at the Habibie Center.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080923e49n0000y\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 LNG Terminal Consortium Allowed to Import Fuel\b0\par\par\uc2 486 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 September 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The government opens an opportunity for the LNG Receiving Terminal consortium in Banten to import 1.5 million tons of fuel to compensate supply shortage to the terminal.\par \par \uc2 The first-stage construction of the receiving terminal-owned by three companies of State Gas Company PGN, State Electricity Company PLN, and State Oil Company-with 1.5 million tons in capacity will be completed by 2012. The consortium also targets to complete its second-stage terminal by 2018. The LNG project is estimated to cost a total investment of US$650 million.\par \par \uc2 Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources Purnomo Yusgiantoro said the department opened opportunities for the consortium to import LNG.\par \par \uc2 The LNG receiving terminal so far has only secured 1.5 million tons in LNG supply from Total Indonesie. According to Purnomo, the government would try to arrange for supplies from Tangguh train III LNG and from Senoro LNG project, Central Sulawesi.\par \par \uc2 The upstream gas agency BP Migas leaves the matter of gas supply to the three state-owned enterprises controlling the project.\par \par \uc2 Deputy for Financial, \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and Marketing at the BP Migas Djoko Harsono revealed the agency so far could only allocate 1.5 million tons of gas from Total Inpex-owned East Kalimantan PSC of a total three million tons needed every year. As for the rest of the supply, he added, the consortium of the three state-owned enterprises should find it themselves.\par \par \uc2 "We have just got supply from East Kal [Kalimantan] PSC, but the rest has yet been confirmed. It is the terminal developer that is supposed to find the supply, not us," he told yesterday after a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  hearing on oil and gas non-\b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  state revenues with the House's Commission XI.\par \par \uc2 According to Djoko, there were three potential gas supply sources, namely Inpex Masela-owned Masela LNG project, Tangguh LNG project, and a gas mega-project on Makassar Straits. However, he inserted, it would probably take a long time to get supply from the three sources.\par \par \uc2 If there was no additional gas supply secured, East Kalimantan PSC gas producer consisting of Total Indonesie, Inpex, Vico, and \uc2 Chevron\uc2 , would be allowed to export their gas supply quota, thus, making the realization of the receiving terminal construction \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 President Director of PGN Hendi P. Santoso confirmed this, saying a memorandum of agreement on LNG from East Kalimantan states the receiving terminal should start construction by 2009.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, he argued, PGN could not force the project to keep running amid stagnant capacity since it would only lead to an uneconomical project.\par \par \uc2 "Between a terminal with a total capacity of 1.5 million tons and that of 3 million tons, the capital need difference is only 10%. If we force the project to keep running, the gas price will be so expensive for the consumers [especially PLN] to afford." (Bisnis/raf/dle)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080924e49o0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Bailout Delay to Add More Victims\b0\par\par\uc2 487 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 September 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: Market players are worried that the US Congress' hesitancy to approve the financial system rescue plan will add more victims other than \uc2 Lehman Brothers\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Senior Investment Manager at Mizuho Asset Management Co. Tsuyoshi Shimizu revealed the decision on bailout \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be made longer than expected, which would be negative for the market. The longer the decision was taken, the larger the number of victims, with \uc2 Washington Mutual Inc\uc2  being the recent victim.\par \par \uc2 "It is assumed the bailout \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be decided longer than expected, which is negative. The longer the decision is taken, the larger the number of victims, with \uc2 Washington Mutual Inc\uc2  being the recent victim," he said as quoted by Bloomberg yesterday.\par \par \uc2 The negotiation to disburse US$700 billion bailout fund to rescue the US financial system is slowing down as several Congress members of the Republic Party viewed the bailout sales value was low.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, the official website of the US Presidential Office informs President Bush stated the US was under a severe \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. Therefore, he called for an issuance of a crisis mitigation law.\par \par \uc2 "I hope we can reach the agreement as soon as possible," told Bush.\par \par \uc2 Bloomberg reported there was an unprecedented meeting that the President invited two presidential candidates, the Congress chairperson, and cabinet members. The brief meeting was later continued until midnight at the Capitol Hill. After that, another meeting was scheduled for Monday morning the US time.\par \par \uc2 The delay in the talk fuels \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the financial market after the US government shuts down \uc2 Washington Mutual\uc2  (\uc2 WaMu\uc2 ) and sells its savings to \uc2 JP Morgan Chase and Co\uc2 . Following the action, \uc2 JP Morgan\uc2  will become the largest bank in the US after it acquires \uc2 WaMu\uc2  branch in New York for US$1.9 billion.\par \par \uc2 Switch fund\par \par \uc2 An analyst at PT Trust Securities Suhendra Wahid viewed the delay in the bailout \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had made global investors choose to withdraw funds from the bourse and switch them to the commodity market.\par \par \uc2 "The markets are waiting for the Congress' decision. If they approve the bailout plan, the markets will rebound. Otherwise, the markets will be flat or even decline," he told Bisnis yesterday.\par \par \uc2 Such an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , added Suhendra, had made the markets, including in Indonesia, more turbulent. Some foreign investors were estimated to switch their portfolios from the capital markets to the commodity ones.\par \par \uc2 However, such a condition had served as a blessing in disguise for the Composite Stock Index (IHSG). Commodity stocks would soar and drive index rally.\par \par \uc2 The IHSG yesterday fell by 23.97 points (1.28%) to 1,846.09, while the Morgan Stanley Capital Asia Pacific index also dropped by 0.6% to 114.10.\par \par \uc2 Stocks on Asian bourse this weekend also declined, such as the Hang Seng index (1.33%), Kospi (1.69%), Nikkei (0.94%), Shanghai (0.16%), and Singapore STI (1.31%). (Bisnis/ags/esu)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080927e49r00001\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 'Spur Real Sector to Deal with Global Slowdown'\b0\par\par\uc2 248 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 September 2008\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 Bisnis Indonesia   \par \par \uc2 JAKARTA: The threat of a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown has to force the government to create conducive investment climate to stimulate the real sector growth since many direct investments have been delayed or cancelled.\par \par \uc2 Bambang Soesatyo, Chairperson of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Monetary Permanent Committee at the Indonesia Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) revealed it had been more difficult for the real sector to grow following a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which shrunk demand for exported products.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, it was estimated that the people would see their purchasing power weakened for a long time, at least until next year when the general election would absorb the people's attention. "Therefore, the government has to immediately recover the real sector."\par \par \uc2 According to him, many direct investment plans had been cancelled or delayed, reflected in the total undisbursed loan of IDR280 trillion as of July 2008.\par \par \uc2 "With the current internal and external conditions, it is hard to expect new investments or expansion."\par \par \uc2 However, Head of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Agency Anggito Abimanyu viewed the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in the US would not shut down Indonesia's export opportunity as Indonesia's export to the US only represented 30% of the total export.\par \par \uc2 "I think the crisis in America doesn't mean our export opportunity is lost entirely."\par \par \uc2 According to him, Japan, Europe, China, and other Asean member countries were still potential to absorb Indonesian exported products since the product prices were competitive. (Bisnis/16)\par \par \uc2 Document BISNIS0020080927e49r00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
