\par\par \b \uc2 The economics of Idul Fitri\b0\par\par\uc2 761 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 September 2008\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2008 The Jakarta Post   \par \par \uc2 Manpower and Transmigration Minister Erman Suparno was quoted by the Indonesiaarab.wordpress.com as saying last Tuesday that over the past few weeks alone, Indonesian workers overseas, notably maids in Singapore, Hong Kong and the Middle East, have sent Rp 4 trillion (US$428 million) in remittances to parents or relatives in their home villages.\par \par \uc2 Those remittances, which were much larger than the usual amount for the same period and quite a significant sum -- given the country's per capita income of only $1,600 -- were made especially to welcome this year's Idul Fitri which begins on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Since the middle of this month, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) has daily deployed several armored trucks, each filled with Rp 2.5 billion in cash, to dispense small bills and coins to people in the Greater Jakarta area in light of the upcoming Lebaran festivities.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  estimates people across the country will need a total of Rp 66 trillion in cash during the weeklong Idul Fitri celebrations because banks will close from Tuesday to Friday. That amount is equivalent to what the nation requires for three months during ordinary times.\par \par \uc2 The weeklong cessation of banking services, however, is only one \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  element of the traditional Idul Fitri celebrations.\par \par \uc2 Idul Fitri is the time of year when millions of people in urban areas across the country make their home-sweet-home journey to celebrate the post-fasting month with their parents and relatives. This moment is culturally so sacred to Muslims, who make up the majority of Indonesia's 230 million people, that they join the mudik (exodus) so they are able to share their wealth and the fruits of their hard toils in the cities with their relatives back home.\par \par \uc2 To the migrants -- street vendors, hawkers, maids, construction workers and even officials, corporate executives and professionals -- mudik is an annual opportunity for retrospection, to rejuvenate family relationships and to once again feel the warmness of family they all miss while working amid the hurly-burly of the cities.\par \par \uc2 The annual exodus back to hometowns or villages also reflects the impact of the country's transformation from a largely agricultural, rural-based \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  into a modern, urban-based one as the population in urban areas is now almost 55 percent.\par \par \uc2 Tens of trillions of rupiah will be pumped into the countryside's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the one week of Idul Fitri festivities as millions of Idul Fitri revelers enjoy their holidays in their villages and city folk share their earnings with family members and show off their material achievements.\par \par \uc2 Mudik thus also serves as a means to redistribute income to the rural areas where most of the absolutely poor people live.\par \par \uc2 The exodus out of Jakarta and its satellite towns began last Friday, as can be seen in the long lines for trains and buses, by the number of people with backpacks jumping into any overloaded transportation vehicle they can find and motorists getting stuck for hours in traffic jams along the Cikampek toll road.\par \par \uc2 Those who cannot comprehend the religious, social and cultural philosophy of the mudik may find it hard to understand as to why people go into so much haggling, pain and inconvenience just for a few days of vacation in their home villages. But for Idul Fitri revelers all the pains and inconveniences are nothing but insignificant rigors of the home-sweet-home journey.\par \par \uc2 The almost 30 percent increase in fuel prices last May and the strong inflationary pressures this has generated have affected the purchasing power of people on a fixed income, but most analysts estimate consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  during this year's Idul Fitri festivities will still be much larger than last year's due to the fairly robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth (6.3 percent).\par \par \uc2 This is really good news for department stores, supermarkets and producers of consumer goods because their sales during the fasting month and the weeklong Lebaran holidays usually account for more than 55 percent of their annual sales.\par \par \uc2 Some may argue that the holiday, though a boon to private consumption -- which, in addition to exports and investments is one of the key drivers of our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth -- may be too long for an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as Indonesia's which still needs to expand in order to absorb the millions who are jobless.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, besides fueling greater private consumption, the \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  spree and merriness during the weeklong Idul Fitri will surely provide a psychological boost to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's perception of our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook amid global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020080929e49t00011\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
